# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: crusades
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] The **1240–1241 Votia campaign** was a military conflict occurring in the winter of 1240 to 1241 in Votia (in the western parts of modern-day Leningrad Oblast).
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] Possibly, some knights with nominal fealty to king Valdemar II of Denmark (died March 1241) participated as well.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] In 1227, the Livonian Brothers of the Sword took advantage of Denmark's weakened state and seized control of the Duchy of Estonia.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] King Valdemar II of Denmark attempted to recover the duchy by appealing to the Roman Curia.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] However, the Curia's response was greatly delayed, and it was not until February 1236 that Pope Gregory IX finally decided in favour of Denmark.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] However, the Brothers of the Sword refused to comply, until the Brothers were themselves weakened by the Battle of Saule in 1236.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] They were compelled to merge with the Teutonic Order and subsequently became the Livonian Order.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] The Treaty of Stensby in 1238 returned all of Estonia to Denmark, with the exception of Järva.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] Additionally, the king of Denmark would receive two-thirds of all future lands conquered from pagans in the region, while the Brothers would receive one-third.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] By 1240, Denmark under Valdemar II, Sweden under Birger Jarl, as well as the Livonian Order, were resolved to initiate a crusade against Votia and Novgorod.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] According to Russian sources only, the Novgorodians defeated a Swedish fleet in the Battle of the Neva in the summer of 1240.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] A force consisting of Germans and Estonians invaded Votia in the winter of 1240–1241.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] They occupied the city of Koporye and built a stone castle in order to secure the territory.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] Further to the south, the villages of Tesov and Sablia were also captured, which only lay 30 *versts* (roughly 30 km) from Veliky Novgorod.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] It is reported in the *Novgorod First Chronicle* (NPL) that the Votians suffered greatly from the campaign.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] The primary motive seems to have been that the Livonian Order regarded Votia as a pagan territory to be conquered and converted, unlike Novgorod, which they appeared to have no military or religious designs against.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] Nevertheless, the move was probably also done in order to cut off Novgorodian access to the southern side of the Gulf of Finland, which would severely impact its foreign trade.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] The 1241 treaty between bishop Henry of Ösel-Wiek and the Teutonic Order established legal and economic regulations in the newly acquired area, and mentions that campaign participants were given fiefdoms and other benefits in Votia.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] According to Fonnesberg-Schmidt (2007), "Votia, the lands north-east of Lake Peipus" (...) "were tributary to Novgorod".
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] On the other hand, Selart (2015) stated that "it is not clear how secure Novgorod's control was in Votia at the time (...) There are a number of references to Votia's dependence on Novgorod from the second half of the 13th century.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] It is nevertheless unknown how much of Votia fell within this dependency c.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] There is no indication that Denmark was involved with this campaign.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] Moreover, on 28 March 1241, king Valdemar II died, causing a succession crisis in Denmark between his sons Eric and Abel over the question of who should succeed Valdemar.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] This situation made it impossible for the Danes to launch any kind of crusade in Estonia, let alone beyond Estonia.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] In late 1241, Aleksandr Yaroslavich of Suzdal returned to Novgorod, leading an army into Votia that defeated the Livonian troops, taking some captive while releasing others.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] The NPL tells that Aleksandr supposedly hanged "the Votian and Chud' traitors".
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] The following year, 1242, the NPL narrates that "German" envoys travelled to Novgorod (when Aleksandr was absent), agreeing to withdraw from "the land of the Vod people, of Luga, Pleskov, and Lotygola".
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] Historian Alexander Basilevsky claimed that it had become clear to Novgorod, that the Crusaders, besides trade, were also interested in conquering new territories.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] As a response to the fall of Pskov, Alexander Nevsky reassumed power.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] The newly arrived prince took the Novgorodian city militia and set out for the occupied Votians, and retook the Livonian castle of Koporye.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] Danish and German prisoners from the fortress were sent to Novgorod.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] Nevsky, along with his brother, Prince Andrey of Suzdal, appeared outside of the Crusader-occupied Pskov and quickly stormed the city.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] The Novgorodians crossed the Velikaya and began burning and pillaging Livonian territory.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] In response, the Livonian coalition raised an army in Livonia and Estonia, under Hermann von Buxhoevden, and met the Novgorodians at the Battle on the Ice.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] It is a matter of scholarly debate what the causes, purposes and effects of the Votia campaign were.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] This tradition emerged from a local cult of veneration in Vladimir at the end of the 13th century, which centred on the role of Aleksandr Yaroslavich in the Novgorodian conflicts of the early 1240s.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] By the 15th century, Aleksandr was given the sobriquet "Nevsky" in reference to the supposed Neva battle, and by the 16th century, he was regarded as a heroic defender of Rus', as well as the Orthodox faith, and the progenitor of the Daniilovichi clan of Muscovy.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] Donner and Jaakkola argued the fact that these campaigns all occurred around the same time, and especially that Aleksandr Yaroslavich participated in all three, could not be a coincidence; therefore, all three events were linked together.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] Most Russian historians, as well as several western European historians, adopted Donner's theory of co-ordination.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] Papal documents and treaties of the time only speak of conquering pagan lands and converting pagans to Catholicism.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] Anti Selart (2001, 2015) and many other historians have argued that if the Votia campaign could be called a "crusade", as the older historiographic tradition would have it, it was merely 'a continuation of the process of Christianization already under way in Estonia.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] Its aim was to conquer the pagan territories and obtain rule over them by means of baptism.
[src:crusades/1240-1241-votia-campaign] The Livonian conquest of Votia might also have seriously harmed Novgorod's commercial interests by taking control of one of its nearby waterways, but whether that was one of its purposes, or consequences, is uncertain.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February 2022, during the Russo-Ukrainian war, Russia launched a full-scale invasion of Ukraine, starting the current phase of the war, the largest conflict in Europe since World War II.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By April 2022, the invasion's initial goal of a rapid Russian victory via decapitation had failed, with Ukraine pushing back the northern arm of the invasion and preventing the capture of Kyiv.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Following this, the war transitioned to more conventional fighting in the south and east of Ukraine.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In a televised address, Russian president Vladimir Putin announced the invasion, calling it a "special military operation".
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] He said that its purpose was to support the Russian-backed breakaway republics of Donetsk and Luhansk, whose paramilitary forces had been fighting Ukraine in the war in Donbas since 2014.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin espoused irredentist and imperialist views challenging Ukraine's legitimacy as a state, baselessly claimed that the Ukrainian government were neo-Nazis committing genocide against the Russian minority in the Donbas, and said that Russia's goal was to "demilitarise and denazify" Ukraine.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In late 2021, Russia massed troops near Ukraine's borders and issued demands to the West including a ban on Ukraine ever joining the NATO military alliance.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After repeatedly denying having plans to attack Ukraine, on 24 February 2022, Russian air strikes and a ground invasion were launched on a northern front from Belarus towards the capital Kyiv, a southern front from Crimea, and an eastern front from the Donbas and towards Kharkiv.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine enacted martial law, ordered a general mobilisation, and severed diplomatic relations with Russia.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion was met with widespread international condemnation.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The United Nations General Assembly passed a resolution condemning the invasion and demanding a full Russian withdrawal.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The International Court of Justice ordered Russia to halt military operations, and the Council of Europe expelled Russia.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Many countries imposed sanctions on Russia and its ally Belarus and provided humanitarian and military aid to Ukraine.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Baltic states and Poland declared Russia a terrorist state.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Protests occurred around the world, with anti-war protesters in Russia being met by mass arrests and greater media censorship.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The International Criminal Court (ICC) opened an investigation into crimes against humanity, war crimes, abduction of Ukrainian children, and genocide against Ukrainians.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The ICC issued arrest warrants for Putin and other Russian officials.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In 2013, Ukraine's parliament overwhelmingly approved finalising an association agreement with the European Union (EU), which had been negotiated for several years.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia put pressure on Ukraine to reject the agreement and imposed economic sanctions on the country.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kremlin adviser Sergei Glazyev warned in September 2013 that if Ukraine signed the EU agreement, Russia would no longer acknowledge Ukraine's borders.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In November, Ukrainian president Viktor Yanukovych suddenly withdrew from signing the agreement, choosing closer ties to the Russian-led Eurasian Economic Union instead.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This coerced withdrawal triggered a wave of protests known as Euromaidan, culminating in the Revolution of Dignity in February 2014.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Despite signing an agreement, Yanukovych fled.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Parliament voted to remove him and he ended up in Russia.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian soldiers with no insignia occupied the Ukrainian territory of Crimea, and seized the Crimean Parliament.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia annexed Crimea in March 2014, after a widely disputed referendum held under occupation.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Pro-Russian protests immediately followed in the Ukrainian cities of Donetsk and Luhansk.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The war in Donbas began in April 2014 when armed Russian mercenaries led by Igor 'Strelkov' Girkin seized Sloviansk and nearby towns.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian troops were covertly involved in the fighting.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Minsk agreements, signed in September 2014 and February 2015, aimed to resolve the conflict, but ceasefires and further negotiations repeatedly failed.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] There was a large Russian military build-up near Ukraine's borders in March and April 2021, and again in both Russia and Belarus from October 2021 onward.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Members of the Russian government, including Putin, denied having plans to attack or invade Ukraine up until the day before the invasion.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] While Russian troops massed on Ukraine's borders, Russia's proxy forces launched thousands of attacks on Ukrainian forces in the Donbas.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Observers from the Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE), which also includes Ukraine and Russia, reported more than 90,000 ceasefire violations throughout 2021; the vast majority in Russian-controlled territory.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In July 2021, Putin published an essay "On the Historical Unity of Russians and Ukrainians", in which he called Ukraine "historically Russian lands" and claimed there is "no historical basis" for the "idea of Ukrainian people as a nation separate from the Russians".
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin was accused of promoting Russian imperialism, historical revisionism and disinformation.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Writing in 2024, Michael McFaul and Robert Person described this essay as representing not only "cynical propaganda" but also Putin's "deeply held and internalized beliefs".
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In December 2021, Russia issued an ultimatum to the West, which included demands that NATO end all activity in its Eastern European member states and ban Ukraine or any other former Soviet state from ever joining the alliance.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia's government said NATO was a threat and warned of a military response if it followed an "aggressive line".
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg replied that "Russia has no veto" on whether Ukraine joins, and "has no right to establish a sphere of influence to try to control their neighbours".
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Several Western political analysts suggested Russia knew that its "unrealistic demands" would be rejected, which would give it a pretext to invade.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Political scientists Michael McFaul and Robert Person said Russia's occupation of Crimea and the Donbas since 2014 had already blocked Ukraine's NATO membership, suggesting that Putin's real aim was to subjugate Ukraine.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] NATO offered to negotiate some of Russia's demands and to improve military transparency, as long as Russia stopped its troop buildup.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The alliance rejected Russia's demand to keep Ukraine out of NATO forever, pointing out that Russia had signed agreements affirming the right of Ukraine and other countries to join alliances.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The US proposed that itself and Russia sign an agreement not to station missiles or troops in Ukraine.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin replied that Russia's demands had been "ignored", and the Russian troop buildup continued.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Western leaders vowed that heavy sanctions would be imposed should Putin choose to invade rather than to negotiate.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] French president Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz met Putin in February 2022 to dissuade him from invading.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] According to Scholz, Putin told him that Ukraine should not be an independent state.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Scholz told Ukrainian president Volodymyr Zelenskyy to declare Ukraine a neutral country and renounce its aspirations to join NATO.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy said Putin had broken agreements and could not be trusted to respect Ukrainian neutrality.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine had been a neutral country in 2014 when Russia occupied Crimea and invaded the Donbas.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 19 February, Zelenskyy made a speech at the Munich Security Conference, calling for Western powers to end their "appeasement" of Putin and give a timeframe for when Ukraine could join NATO.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Political analysts Taras Kuzio and Vladimir Socor agree that "when Russia made its decision to invade Ukraine, that country was more remote than ever not only from NATO membership but from any track that might lead to membership".
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Fighting in Donbas escalated from 17 February 2022.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Ukrainians and the Russian separatists accused one another of firing into their respective territories.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 18 February, the Donetsk and Luhansk people's republics ordered all civilians to leave their capitals, although observers noted that full evacuations would take months.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian media reported a sharp increase in artillery shelling by the Russian-led militants in Donbas as an attempt to provoke the Ukrainian army.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Separatist leaders warned that Ukraine was about to launch an offensive, but they gave no evidence, and *The Guardian* noted it would be "exceedingly risky" for Ukraine to assault the Donbas while Russian troops were massed on its borders.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy said his military would not respond to the provocations.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the days leading up to the invasion, the Russian government intensified its disinformation campaign.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine and Western leaders accused Russia of staging false flag attacks to give Russia a pretext for invading.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian state media aired fabricated videos that purported to show Ukrainian forces attacking Russians in Donbas; evidence showed that the claimed attacks, explosions, and evacuations were staged by Russia.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 17 February, Russian proxy forces shelled a kindergarten and blamed it on Ukraine, although the kindetgarten was in Ukrainian-held territory.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 21 February, the head of the Russian Federal Security Service (FSB) said that Russian forces had killed five Ukrainian "saboteurs" that crossed into Russian territory, capturing one Ukrainian serviceman and destroying two armoured vehicles.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The claim was denied by Ukraine and drew warnings that Russia was seeking further justification to start an invasion.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 21 February, Putin announced that the Russian government would recognise the Donetsk and Luhansk people's republics.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The same evening, Putin directed that Russian troops be deployed to the Donbas, in what he called a "peacekeeping mission".
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the same speech, Putin questioned the validity of the Ukrainian nation, stating that "Modern Ukraine was entirely created by Russia", views which Michael McFaul and Robert Person, writing in 2024, described as "grotesque".
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The 21 February intervention in Donbas was condemned by several members of the UN Security Council; none voiced support.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 22 February, video footage shot in the early morning showed Russian armed forces and tanks moving in the Donbas region.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Federation Council unanimously authorised the use of military force outside Russia.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In response, Zelenskyy ordered the conscription of army reservists.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The following day, Ukraine's parliament proclaimed a 30-day nationwide state of emergency and ordered the mobilisation of all reservists.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia began to evacuate its embassy in Kyiv.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The websites of the Ukrainian parliament and government, along with banking websites, were hit by DDoS attacks, widely attributed to Russian-backed hackers.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On the night of 23 February, Zelenskyy gave a speech in Russian in which he appealed to the citizens of Russia to prevent war.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] He also refuted Russia's claims about the presence of neo-Nazis in the Ukrainian government and said that he had no intention of attacking the Donbas region.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov said on 23 February that the separatist leaders in Donetsk and Luhansk had sent a letter to Putin stating that Ukrainian shelling had caused civilian deaths and appealing for Russian military support.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In response, Ukraine requested an urgent UN Security Council meeting.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Half an hour into the emergency meeting, Putin announced the start of military operations in Ukraine.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Sergiy Kyslytsya, the Ukrainian representative, subsequently called on the Russian representative, Vasily Nebenzya, to "do everything possible to stop the war" or relinquish his position as president of the UN Security Council; Nebenzya refused.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The decision to invade was reportedly made by Putin and a small group of war hawks or *siloviki* in Putin's inner circle, including national security adviser Nikolai Patrushev and defence minister Sergei Shoigu.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After the start of the invasion, Ukrainian and Western analysts assessed that Putin seemed to have believed that the Russian Armed Forces would be capable of seizing Kyiv within days.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This assessment led to the conclusion that "taking Kyiv in three days" had been the original goal of the invasion.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The narrative of the planned "three day" capture of Kyiv was reinforced by statements by Aleksandr Lukashenko and Margarita Simonyan, editor-in-chief of Russian state-controlled broadcaster RT.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March, the Security Service of Ukraine (SBU) repeated the claim following its release of a video showing a captured Russian soldier claiming that his unit was sent into Ukraine with food supplies for only three days.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Documents found inside Russian tanks mention how the "special military operation" would conclude in ten days.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine also captured "flagship" tanks – as used in parades – along with military parade uniforms, suggesting that Russia expected to stage a victory parade in Kyiv after a swift conquest.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin himself asserted back in 2014 that Russian forces "could take Ukraine in two weeks".
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Three days after the invasion began, RIA Novosti, a Russian state news agency, mistakenly published an article called "Russia's Coming and the New World", which had been made in advance in anticipation of a Russian victory; it announced that "Ukraine had returned to Russia".
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy also said that Russia had sent him an ultimatum to step down and be replaced with Viktor Medvedchuk.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kyiv time on 24 February, Putin, in another speech, announced a "special military operation", which effectively declared war on Ukraine.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin said the operation was to "protect the people" of the Russian-controlled breakaway republics.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] He said Russia sought the "demilitarisation and denazification" of Ukraine, and denied the legitimacy of the Ukrainian state.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin said he had no plans to occupy Ukraine.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion began within minutes of Putin's speech.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In order to justify the invasion of Ukraine within the context of international norms, Putin cited the 1999 NATO bombing of Yugoslavia and 2003 US invasion of Iraq.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian regular forces involved in the invasion comprised nearly 150,000 troops, organised in about 140 Battalion Tactical Groups.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The forces of the Russia-controlled LNR and DNR, and paramilitary forces engaged in the invasion, raised total Russian-controlled forces employed in the campaign to as many as 200,000.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] These forces were organised into groups having tactical signs to distinguish them, and were to advance into Ukraine along at least ten different axes of advance.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Rather than having a unified command-structure, these groups were organised under different Russian military-district command-posts named after the region of Russia in which their respective military-district was located.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Three groups, all having the tactical sign "Z" and commanded by the Western Military District under Alexander Zhuravlyov, were to advance into Ukraine respectively from Kursk, Belgorod and Voronezh.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Groups under the Southern Military District under Aleksandr Dvornikov were identified with a "Z in a square" tactical symbol, and, advancing from occupied Crimea, were tasked with surrounding Mariupol, capturing Zaporizhia, seizing Kherson, and crossing the Dnieper river to take Voznesensk.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian regular forces involved in the invasion were equipped with roughly 2,800 tanks ready for combat, with another 400 approximately in the hands of the Russian-controlled proxy forces of the LNR and DNR.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian forces at the outbreak of the war comprised roughly 20 combat-ready brigades, of which more than half were located in the east of the country, positioned along the line of contact in the "Joint Forces Operation" zone in Donbas.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] An additional manoeuvre brigade and two brigades of artillery were located in the Kyiv region, with other forces also deployed in the area of Kharkiv, Dnipro, Sumy, and Odesa.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] No major combat units were located on the Gomel or Crimean axes.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian tank-forces had roughly 900 battle-ready tanks organised in some 30 battalions at the time of the invasion.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Most of these tank battalions were formed in the period 2014–2018, when roughly 500 tanks were delivered to the Ukrainian armed forces, mostly reconditioned older tanks rather than new-built tanks, particularly T-64B and T-64-BM tanks.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The tank battalions were spread between Ukraine's two regular and four reserve armoured brigades, as well as tank units attached to brigades of mechanised, mountain, airborne and marine infantry.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In contrast to the direct-fire techniques practised in most armoured forces, Ukrainian forces had, based on their experience during the war in Donbas, developed a technique of using tanks in the indirect-fire role.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This meant Ukrainian tank forces acting essentially as mobile artillery that did not require the kind of screening that traditional artillery units require.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion began at dawn on 24 February.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Fighting began in Luhansk Oblast at 3:40 a.m.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kyiv time near Milove on the border with Russia.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The main infantry and tank attacks were launched in four spearheads, creating a northern front launched towards Kyiv from Belarus, a southern front from Crimea, a southeastern front from Russian-controlled Donbas, and an eastern front from Russia towards Kharkiv and Sumy.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian vehicles were subsequently marked with a white *Z* military symbol (a non-Cyrillic letter), believed to be a measure to prevent friendly fire.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Immediately after the invasion began, Zelenskyy declared martial law in Ukraine in a first video speech.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The same evening, he ordered a general mobilisation of all Ukrainian males between 18 and 60 years old, prohibiting them from leaving the country.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Wagner Group mercenaries and Kadyrovites contracted by the Kremlin reportedly made several attempts to assassinate Zelenskyy, including an operation involving several hundred mercenaries meant to infiltrate Kyiv with the aim of killing the Ukrainian president.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Ukrainian government said anti-war officials within Russia's FSB shared the plans with them.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy appeared defiant in video messages on 24 through 26 February, that he and his cabinet is still in Kyiv.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 26 February NATO met and its countries pledged military aid for Ukraine and on 27 February Germany called the invasion a historic watershed.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] That day in the evening Putin put Russia's nuclear deterrence into alert.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russian invasion was unexpectedly met by fierce Ukrainian resistance.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In Kyiv, Russia failed to take the city and was repulsed in the battles of Irpin, Hostomel, and Bucha.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russians tried to encircle the capital, but its defenders under Oleksandr Syrskyi held their ground, effectively using Western Javelin anti-tank missiles and Stinger anti-aircraft missiles to thin Russian supply lines and stall the offensive.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On the southern front, Russian forces had captured the regional capital of Kherson by 2 March.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A column of Russian tanks and armoured vehicles was ambushed on 9 March outside of Brovary and sustained heavy losses that forced them to retreat.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russian army adopted siege tactics on the western front around the key cities of Chernihiv, Sumy and Kharkiv, but failed to capture them due to stiff resistance and logistical setbacks.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In Mykolaiv Oblast, Russian forces advanced as far as Voznesensk, but were repelled and pushed back south of Mykolaiv.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A second axis, deployed towards eastern Kyiv from Russia by the Central Military District (northeastern front), comprised the 41st Combined Arms Army and the 2nd Guards Combined Arms Army.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A third axis was deployed towards Kharkiv by the Western Military District (eastern front), with the 1st Guards Tank Army and 20th Combined Arms Army.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 7 April, Russian troops deployed to the northern front by the Russian Eastern Military District pulled back from the Kyiv offensive, reportedly to resupply and redeploy to the Donbas region in an effort to reinforce the renewed invasion of southeastern Ukraine.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The northeastern front, including the Central Military District, was similarly withdrawn for resupply and redeployment to southeastern Ukraine.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian efforts to capture Kyiv included a probative spearhead on 24 February, from Belarus south along the west bank of the Dnipro River.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The apparent intent was to encircle the city from the west, supported by two separate axes of attack from Russia along the east bank of the Dnipro: the western at Chernihiv, and from the east at Sumy.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] These were likely intended to encircle Kyiv from the northeast and east.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia tried to seize Kyiv quickly, with Spetsnaz infiltrating into the city supported by airborne operations and a rapid mechanised advance from the north, but failed.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Reporter Glenn Kessler said it came from "a single source, but on the surface it appears to be a good one".
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces advancing on Kyiv from Belarus gained control of the ghost town of Chernobyl.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian Airborne Forces attempted to seize two key airfields near Kyiv, launching an airborne assault on Antonov Airport, and a similar landing at Vasylkiv, near Vasylkiv Air Base, on 26 February.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By early March, further Russian advances along the west side of the Dnipro were limited, after suffering setbacks from Ukrainian defence.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] As of 5 March, a large Russian convoy, reportedly 64 kilometres (40 mi) in length, had made little progress toward Kyiv.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The London-based think tank Royal United Services Institute (RUSI) assessed the Russian performance from the north and east as "stalled".
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Advances along the Chernihiv axis had largely halted as a siege of the city began.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces also continued advancing from the northwest of Kyiv, capturing Bucha, Hostomel, and Vorzel by 5 March, though Irpin remained contested as of 9 March.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 11 March, it was reported that the lengthy convoy had largely dispersed, taking up positions that offered tree cover.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 16 March, Ukrainian forces began a counter-offensive to repel Russian forces approaching Kyiv from several surrounding cities.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 20 March, the Russian military appeared to be waging a rapid invasion to achieve its apparent primary goal of the seizure of Kyiv, along with the occupation of Eastern Ukraine and the overthrow of the Ukrainian government.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Unable to achieve a quick victory in Kyiv, Russian forces switched strategies and began using standoff weapons, indiscriminate bombing, and siege warfare.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 March, the Ukrainian counteroffensive in Kyiv resulted in several towns, including Makariv, being retaken to the east and west of Kyiv.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] As part of a general retreat of Russian forces north of Kyiv, as well as attacks on Russian formations by the Ukrainian military, Russian troops in the Bucha area retreated north by the end of March.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian forces entered the city on 1 April.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine claimed to recapture the entire region around Kyiv, including Irpin, Bucha, and Hostomel, by 2 April, with evidence of war crimes being uncovered in Bucha.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces advanced into Chernihiv Oblast on 24 February, besieging its administrative capital within four days of fighting.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 February Ukrainian forces lost control over Konotop.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces also attacked Okhtyrka, deploying thermobaric weapons.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 4 March, Frederick Kagan wrote that the Sumy axis was then "the most successful and dangerous Russian avenue of advance on Kyiv", and commented that the geography favoured mechanised advances as the terrain "is flat and sparsely populated, offering few good defensive positions".
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Travelling along highways, Russian forces reached Brovary, an eastern suburb of Kyiv, on 4 March.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Pentagon confirmed on 6 April that the Russian army had left Chernihiv Oblast, but Sumy Oblast remained contested.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 7 April, the governor of Sumy Oblast said that Russian troops were gone, but had left behind rigged explosives and other hazards.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February, Russian forces took control of the North Crimean Canal, allowing Crimea to obtain water from the Dnieper, which had been cut off since 2014.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 26 February, the siege of Mariupol began as the attack moved east linking to separatist-held Donbas.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] En route, Russian forces entered Berdiansk and captured it.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 February, Russian units from the DPR were fighting near Pavlopil as they moved on Mariupol.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By evening, the Russian Navy began an amphibious assault on the coast of the Sea of Azov 70 kilometres (43 mi) west of Mariupol.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A US defence official said that Russian forces were deploying thousands of marines from this beachhead.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russian 22nd Army Corps approached the Zaporizhzhia Nuclear Power Plant on 26 February and besieged Enerhodar.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A fire began, but the Ukrainian military said that essential equipment was undamaged.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A third Russian attack group from Crimea moved northwest and captured the bridge over the Dnieper.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March, Russian troops took Kherson; this was the first major city to fall to Russian forces.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian troops moved on Mykolaiv and attacked it two days later.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After renewed missile attacks on 14 March in Mariupol, the Ukrainian government said more than 2,500 had died.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 18 March, Mariupol was completely encircled and fighting reached the city centre, hampering efforts to evacuate civilians.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 20 March, an art school sheltering around 400 people, was destroyed by Russian bombs.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russians demanded surrender, and the Ukrainians refused.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin told Emmanuel Macron in a phone call on 29 March that the bombardment of Mariupol would only end when the Ukrainians surrendered.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 1 April, Russian troops refused safe passage into Mariupol to 50 buses sent by the United Nations to evacuate civilians, as peace talks continued in Istanbul.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 3 April, following the retreat of Russian forces from Kyiv, Russia expanded its attack on southern Ukraine further west, with bombardment and strikes against Odesa, Mykolaiv, and the Zaporizhzhia Nuclear Power Plant.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the east, Russian troops attempted to capture Kharkiv, less than 35 kilometres (22 mi) from the Russian border, and met strong Ukrainian resistance.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 February, the Millerovo air base was attacked by Ukrainian military forces with OTR-21 Tochka missiles, which according to Ukrainian officials, destroyed several Russian Air Force planes and started a fire.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 1 March, Denis Pushilin, head of the DPR, announced that DPR forces had almost completely surrounded the city of Volnovakha.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March, Russian forces were repelled from Sievierodonetsk during an attack against the city.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On the same day, Ukrainian forces initiated a counter-offensive on Horlivka, controlled by the DPR.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Izium was captured by Russian forces on 1 April after a monthlong battle.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 March, the Russian defence ministry said it would seek to occupy major cities in eastern Ukraine.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 31 March, *PBS News* reported renewed shelling and missile attacks in Kharkiv, as bad or worse than before, as peace talks with Russia were to resume in Istanbul.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Amid the heightened Russian shelling of Kharkiv on 31 March, Russia reported a helicopter strike against an oil supply depot approximately 35 kilometres (22 mi) north of the border in Belgorod, and accused Ukraine of the attack.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 14 March, Russian forces conducted multiple cruise missile attacks on a military training facility in Yavoriv, Lviv Oblast, close to the Polish border.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Local governor Maksym Kozytskyy reported that at least 35 people had been killed in the attacks.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 18 March, Russia expanded the attack to Lviv, with Ukrainian military officials saying initial information suggested that the missiles which hit Lviv were likely air-launched cruise missiles originating from warplanes flying over the Black Sea.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February, Russian forces attacked the Chuhuiv air base, which housed Bayraktar TB2 drones.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The attack caused damage to fuel storage areas and infrastructure.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The next day, the Millerovo air base was attacked by Ukrainian military forces using OTR-21 Tochka missiles.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] According to Ukrainian officials, this destroyed several Russian Air Force planes and set the airbase on fire.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the Zhytomyr Airport attack on 27 February, it was reported that Russia used 9K720 Iskander missile systems, located in Belarus, to attack the civilian Zhytomyr Airport.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia lost at least ten aircraft on 5 March.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 6 March, the General Staff of the Armed Forces of Ukraine reported that 88 Russian aircraft had been destroyed since the war began.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] However, an anonymous senior US defence official told Reuters on 7 March that Russia still had the "vast majority" of its fighter jets and helicopters that had been amassed near Ukraine available to fly.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After the first month of the invasion, Justin Bronk, a British military observer, counted the Russian aircraft losses at 15 fixed-wing aircraft and 35 helicopters, but noted that the true total was certainly higher.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 13 March, Russian forces conducted multiple cruise missile attacks on a military training facility in Yavoriv, Lviv Oblast, close to the Polish border.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine lies on the Black Sea, which only has access through the Turkish-held Bosphorus and Dardanelles straits.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 28 February, Turkey invoked the 1936 Montreux Convention and sealed off the straits to Russian warships not registered as having Black Sea home bases and not returning to their ports of origin.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This prevented the passage of four Russian naval vessels through the Turkish Straits.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February, the State Border Guard Service of Ukraine announced that an attack on Snake Island by Russian Navy ships had begun.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The cruiser *Moskva* and patrol boat *Vasily Bykov* bombarded the island with their deck guns.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] When the Russian warship identified itself and instructed the Ukrainian soldiers stationed on the island to surrender, their response was "Russian warship, go fuck yourself!" After the bombardment, a detachment of Russian soldiers landed and took control of Snake Island.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia stated on 26 February that US drones were supplying intelligence to the Ukrainian navy to help target Russian warships in the Black Sea, which the US denied.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 3 March, the Ukrainian frigate *Hetman Sahaidachny*, the flagship of the Ukrainian navy, was scuttled in Mykolaiv to prevent its capture by Russian forces.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 14 March, the Russian source RT reported that the Russian Armed Forces had captured about a dozen Ukrainian ships in Berdiansk, including the *Polnocny*-class landing ship *Yuri Olefirenko*.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 March, Ukrainian officials said that a Russian landing ship docked in Berdiansk was destroyed by a Ukrainian rocket attack.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Military analysts have been highly critical of the Russian plan of invasion.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kofman also criticised the use of "thunder runs" similar to those used by US forces in the 2003 Iraq war, in an environment where resistance to such attempts to go around urban centres was likely to be far higher.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The November 2022 Royal United Services Institute (RUSI) report on the invasion also criticised the invasion plan as being based on "false assumptions", and spreading Russian forces too thinly across too many objectives, with insufficient contingency-planning for what to do if things went wrong.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Nevertheless, RUSI also stated that "If competently executed, these plans could have succeeded".
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Writing in 2024 in the *Journal of Strategic Studies*, analysts from the Swiss Military Academy at ETH Zurich characterised the invasion plan as being "predicated on a rapid, decisive overthrow of the government in Kyiv, presuming minimal resistance".
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] They also criticised what they saw as the excessively rigid, Soviet-style command structure and operational planning of Russian forces during the invasion.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian air forces during the campaign were described by military analyst Sean M.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Wiswesser, writing in 2023 in the *Small Wars & Insurgencies* journal, as having "bungled air operations from the outset of the war".
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Wiswesser described the Russian air forces as having "settled largely for a 'tie'" during the period of the invasion.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The force-structure of Russian forces during the invasion has also been criticised, particularly the use of battalion tactical groups (BTGs), which proved brittle once Ukrainian resistance was met.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Whilst praising Ukraine's resistance to the invasion, analysts have also identified deficiencies in the deployment of Ukrainian forces before the invasion.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] At the tactical level, however, RUSI assessed Ukrainian forces as comprising "units which had been psychologically and practically preparing for this fight for eight years".
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Alexander Hill described Ukrainian forces as having undergone a transformation since the fighting of 2014, and having become "a stubborn opponent that was typically difficult [for Russian troops] to dislodge".
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces did not deploy an overall commander for the invasion of Ukraine, with command divided between the military district commanders, each of whom was assigned to their own axis of attack.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] According to Mason Clark of the Institute for the Study of War, this resulted in commanders competing for central resources and each effectively fighting their own war.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Subsequent to the failure of this strategy, according to Clark, Putin appointed Aleksandr Dvornikov as an overall commander in Ukraine on 8 April 2022, however Dvornikov retained his post as commander of the Southern Military District.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Disatisfied with Dvornikov's performance, according to Clark, Putin then dismissed Dvornikov as overall commander in June 2022 but allowed him to remain in overall command for several weeks, before Gennady Zhidko was reportedly appointed to that role.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] However, according to Clark, both Zhidko and Dvornikov were effectively "first among equals" among the Russian Military District Commanders rather than true theatre commanders, and it was not until October 2022 that a dedicated theatre commander - Sergey Surovikin - was appointed.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia abandoned the attempt to take Kyiv in early April, but a lasting state of war between Russia and Ukraine remained, with Russia capturing Mariupol by 20 May 2022, and maintaining an occupation of large portions of four Ukrainian oblasts—Donetsk, Kherson, Luhansk, and Zaporizhzhia.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In August, Ukrainian forces began liberating territories in the north-east and south.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 30 September 2022, Russia declared the annexation of the four partially-occupied oblasts, which was internationally condemned.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Most of Luhansk Oblast and part of Donetsk Oblast had been controlled by pro-Russian separatists since 2014, while the Kherson and Zaporizhzhia oblasts were invaded by Russia in 2022.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The boundaries of the areas to be annexed and their borders were not defined; Russian officials stated that they would be defined later.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] None of the oblasts were fully under Russian control at the time of the declaration, nor since.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] If limited to the areas then under Russian control (about 90,000 km2 or 15% of Ukraine's territory, roughly the size of Portugal) the annexation would still be the largest in Europe since World War II.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In other respects as well—in terms of the scale and intensity of hostilities, and the number of casualties—after the invasion, the war became the biggest war in Europe since World War II.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] From then through 2023, Russian offensives and Ukrainian counteroffensives gained only small amounts of territory.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The war has also led to attacks in Russia by Ukrainian and Ukrainian-backed forces, among them a cross-border offensive into Russia's Kursk region in August 2024.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia has repeatedly carried out deliberate and indiscriminate attacks on civilians far from the frontline.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The International Criminal Court (ICC) opened an investigation into war crimes and issued arrest warrants for Putin and several other Russian officials.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion received widespread international condemnation from governments and intergovernmental organisations.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March 2022 and on 23 February 2023, 141 member states of the UN General Assembly voted for a resolution saying that Russia should immediately withdraw.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Seven, including Russia, voted against the measure.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Political reactions to the invasion included new sanctions imposed on Russia, which triggered widespread economic effects on the Russian and world economies.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Sanctions forced Russia to reorient its oil exports to non-sanctioning countries such as India, rely more on LNG (which was not subject to European Union sanctions), and shift its coal exports from Europe to Asia.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Most European countries cancelled nuclear cooperation with Russia.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Over seventy sovereign states and the European Union delivered humanitarian aid to Ukraine, and nearly fifty countries plus the EU provided military aid.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Economic sanctions included a ban on Russian aircraft using EU airspace, a ban of certain Russian banks from the SWIFT international payments system, and a ban on certain Russian media outlets.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Reactions to the invasion have included public response, media responses, peace efforts, and the examination of the legal implications of the invasion.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Some countries, particularly in the Global South, saw public sympathy or outright support for Russia, due in part to distrust of US foreign policy.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Protests and demonstrations were held worldwide, including some in Russia and parts of Ukraine occupied by Russia.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Calls for a boycott of Russian goods spread on social media platforms, while hackers attacked Russian websites, particularly those operated by the Russian government.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Anti-Russian sentiment against Russians living abroad surged after the invasion.
[src:crusades/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In March 2022, Russian's parliament introduced prison sentences of up to 15 years for publishing "fake news" about Russian military operations, intended to suppress any criticism related to the war.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] Abaqa was born in Mongolia on 27 February 1234, son of Ilkhanate founder Hulagu Khan.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] A favoured son of Hulagu, he was made governor of Turkestan.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] Before his death, he had been negotiating with the Byzantine Emperor Michael VIII Palaiologos to add a daughter of the Byzantine imperial family to Hulagu's number of wives.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] Michael VIII had selected his illegitimate daughter Maria Palaiologina, who was dispatched in 1265, escorted by the abbot of Pantokrator monastery, Theodosius de Villehardouin.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] Historian Steven Runciman relates how she was accompanied by the Patriarch Euthymius of Antioch.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] Since Hulagu died before she arrived, she was instead married to Hulagu's son, Abaqa.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] He received her hand in marriage when he was installed as Ilkhan.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] When Hulagu's wife Doquz Khatun also died in 1265, the role of spiritual leader transferred to Maria, who was called "Despina Khatun" by the Mongols.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] It was Abaqa who decided that the permanent location for the Ilkhanate capital would be Tabriz, which was in the northwestern grasslands that the Mongols preferred.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] Abaqa took power four months after the death of his father, and then spent the next several months redistributing fiefs and governorships.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] Some of the coins from Abaqa's era display the Christian cross, and bear in Arabic the Christian inscription "In the name of the Father, the Son and the Holy Spirit, only one God".
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] Since Hulagu's reign, the Mongols of the Ilkhanate had been at war with the Mongols of the Golden Horde.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] This continued into Abaqa's reign, and the Golden Horde invaded the Ilkhanate in the spring after his accession.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] The invasion was partly due to an alliance between the Golden Horde and the Egyptian Mamluks.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] As part of this alliance, the Golden Horde attempted to distract Abaqa through attacks on his territories so as to keep him from invading Mamluk-held Syria.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] The hostilities continued until the death of the Golden Horde's khan, Berke, in 1267.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] The Great Khan Kublai attempted to intervene to stop the civil war, and due to his influence, the Golden Horde's new khan, Möngke Temür did not launch a major invasion into Abaqa's territory.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] However, Möngke Temür still commanded Commander Nogai to establish an alliance with the Egyptian Mamluk sultan Baibars promising that he would attack Abaqa and share any conquered territories.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] But, at the same time, Möngke Temür sent envoys to congratulate Abaqa when the Ilkhan defeated Ghiyas-ud-din Baraq.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] In 1270, he allowed Mengu-Timur to collect his revenues from workshops in Iran.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] Ögedei's grandson Kaidu, Batu's grandson Mengu-Timur and Baraq of the Chagatai Khanate formed an alliance against Kublai Khan and Abaqa in Talas.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] They appointed Kaidu a ruler of Central Asia.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] The resulting Kaidu–Kublai war which started in 1268 would carry on until the end of the century.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] In 1270, Baraq Khan of the Chagatai Khanate tried to annex Iran, which resulted in an attack on Abaqa who was in the city of Herat.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] However, Abaqa was able to launch a successful defence and also defeated Baraq's relative Teguder in Georgia.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] In the following year, he retaliated by sending an army against the Chagatai Khanate.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] They plundered Bukhara and surrounding areas.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] There were small conflicts between Abaqa and the Qara'unas who were under the control of Chagatai nobles until 1280.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] Abaqa was one in a long line of Mongol rulers who attempted to secure Western co-operation against the Muslim Mamluks.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] He corresponded with Pope Clement IV during 1267–1268, and reportedly sent a Mongol ambassador to western Europe in 1268, trying to form a Franco-Mongol alliance between his forces, those of the West, and those of his father-in-law Michael VIII.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] He received responses from Rome and from James I of Aragon, though it is unclear if this was what led to James' unsuccessful expedition to Acre in 1269.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] Abaqa is recorded as having written to the Aragonese king, saying that he was going to send his brother, Aghai, to join the Aragonese when they arrived in Cilicia.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] But neither this diplomatic mission, nor two further embassies to Europe in 1276 and 1277, brought any tangible results.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] In 1260 Bohemond VI of Antioch was persuaded by his father-in-law, Hetoum I of Armenia, to voluntarily submit to Mongol authority while Abaqa's father Hulagu was in power, making Antioch and Tripoli vassal states of the Ilkhanate.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] In 1268, the Mamluk leader Baibars captured Antioch, and Bohemond obtained a truce with Baibars in order to avoid losing Tripoli.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] In response to the fall of Antioch, Edward I of England arrived in Acre in 1271, trying to lead a new Crusade.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] It was ultimately considered a military failure, but Edward was able to eventually secure a truce with the Mamluks before he had to return to England.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] When Edward arrived in Acre, he had sent an embassy to Abaqa, led by Reginald Rossel, Godefroi of Waus and John of Parker, requesting military assistance from the Mongols.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] — Letter from Abaqa to Edward I, 4 September 1271.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] The Mongols, including some auxiliary Seljuk troops, ravaged the land from Aleppo southward.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] Though the force was relatively small, they triggered an exodus of the Muslim population (who remembered the previous campaigns of the Mongol general Kitbuqa) as far south as Cairo.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] Edward, for his part, was never able to muster his own forces to coordinate actions with the Mongols or even achieve any military victories, so Abaqa's forces eventually withdrew.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] When Baibars mounted a counter-offensive from Egypt on 12 November 1271, the Mongols had already retreated beyond the Euphrates.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] During 1280 and 1281, Abaqa promoted new attacks against Syria.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] In September 1280, the Mongols occupied Baghras and Darbsak, and took Aleppo on October 20.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] The Mongols sent envoys to Acre to request military support for their campaign, but the Crusaders were still in a 10-year truce with the Mamluks.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] The Vicar of the Patriarch declined Abaqa's request, saying that the city was suffering from hunger, and that the king of Jerusalem was embroiled in another war.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] The King of Cyprus Hugh III and Bohemond VII mobilised their armies, but could not intervene because the Mamluks had already positioned themselves between them and the Mongols.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] Abaqa and Leo III urged the Franks to start a new Crusade, but only the Hospitallers and Edward I (who could not come for lack of funds) responded favourably.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] The Hospitallers of Marqab made combined raids into the Buqaia, and won several engagements against the Sultan Qalawun, raiding as far as the Krak des Chevaliers in October 1280, and defeating the Mamluk army of the Krak in February 1281.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] The Mongols finally retreated, pledging to come back for the winter of 1281.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] They informed the Franks that they would bring 50,000 Mongol horsemen and 50,000 Mongol infantry, but apparently this pledge did not receive a response.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] The Egyptian Muslims had respected a 10-year truce with the Crusaders which began in 1271.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] On 3 May 1281, the new Muslim sultan Qalawun signed a new 10-year truce with the barons of Acre and a second 10-year truce with Bohemond VII of Tripoli, on 16 July 1281.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] The announced Mongol invasion started in September 1281.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] They were joined by the Armenians under Leo III, and by about 200 Hospitalier knights from the fortress of Marqab who considered they were not bound by the truce with the Mamluks.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] On 30 October 1281, 50,000 Mongol troops, together with 30,000 Armenians, Georgians, Greeks and the Frankish Hospitalier Knights of Marqab, fought against the Muslim leader Qalawun at the Second Battle of Homs, but were beaten back.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] Abaqa died at Hamadan on 4 April 1282, probably in a state of delirium tremens.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] This illness was probably caused by too much consumption of alcohol, a habit common to many Mongol leaders.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] However, in 1285, his minister of finance Shams ad-Din Juvayni was accused of having had him poisoned.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] After Abaqa's death, his widow Maria fled back to Constantinople where her father, apparently wishing to spare his capital the fate that befell Baghdad, tried to marry her off again to another Mongol khan.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] Maria would not accept the offer, became a nun, and in about 1285 founded the church of Panagia Mouchliotissa.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] Abaqa was succeeded by his brother Tekuder, who despite his earlier conflicts with the Egyptian Mamluks, had converted to Islam.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] Tekuder reversed Abaqa's pro-Christian policies and proposed an alliance with the Mamluk Sultan Qalawun, who resumed attacks on Frankish territory, capturing the northern fortress of Margat in 1285, Lattakia in 1287, and Tripoli in 1289.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] In 1284, Abaqa's son Arghun led a successful revolt, backed by Kublai.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] Arghun had his uncle Tekuder executed and took power himself, returning to the pro-Christian policies of Abaqa.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] A younger son, Gaykhatu, assumed the throne in 1291.
[src:crusades/abaqa-khan] Padishah Khatun — daughter of Qutb-ud-din Muhammad, ruler of Kirman and Kutlugh Turkan; was given Yesunchin Khatun's (d.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The **Abbasid Caliphate** or **Abbasid Empire** was the third Islamic caliphate, ruled by the Abbasid dynasty.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The dynasty was descended from Muhammad's uncle, Abbas ibn Abd al-Muttalib (d.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Abbasids rose to power in 750, when the Abbasid Revolution overthrew the preceding Umayyad Caliphate, and they ruled as caliphs from their metropole in Iraq until 1258, with Baghdad as their capital for most of their history.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Abbasid Revolution had its origins and first successes in the easterly region of Khurasan, far from the Levantine center of Umayyad influence.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Abbasids first centered their government in Kufa, Iraq, but in 762 the second caliph al-Mansur founded the city of Baghdad and made it the capital.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Baghdad became a center of science, culture, arts, and invention, ushering in what became known as the Golden Age of Islam.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] It hosted several key academic institutions, such as the House of Wisdom, as well as a multi-ethnic and multi-religious population, which made the city famous as a centre of learning across the world.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Abbasid period was marked by the use of bureaucrats in government, including the vizier, as well as a growing inclusion of non-Arab Muslims in the *ummah* (Muslim community) and among the political elites.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The height of Abbasid power and prestige is traditionally associated with the reign of Harun al-Rashid (r.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] After his death, a civil war brought new divisions and was followed by significant changes to the character of the state, including the creation of a new professional army recruited mainly from Turkic slaves and the construction of a new capital, Samarra, in 836.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The 9th century also saw many provinces becoming increasingly autonomous, giving rise to local dynasties that controlled different regions of the empire, such as the Aghlabids, Tahirids, Samanids, Saffarids, and Tulunids.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] After a period of turmoil in the 860s, the caliphate regained some stability and its seat returned to Baghdad in 892.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] During the 10th century, the caliphs were reduced to mere figureheads, with real political and military power resting in the hands of the Iranian Buyids and the Seljuq Turks, who took control of Baghdad in 945 and 1055, respectively.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Abbasids eventually regained control of Iraq during the reign of Caliph al-Muqtafi (r.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] 1136–1160) and extended their rule into Iran during the reign of Caliph al-Nasir (r.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] This revival ended in 1258 with the sack of Baghdad by the Mongols under Hulagu Khan and the execution of Caliph al-Musta'sim, which marked the effective end of the Abbasid Caliphate.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] A surviving branch of the Abbasid dynasty was formally reinstated in 1261 by the Mamluk sultans in Cairo, but it lacked any political power.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The dynasty continued to claim symbolic authority until the Ottoman conquest of Egypt in 1517, the last Abbasid caliph being al-Mutawakkil III.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Abbasid caliphs descended from Abbas ibn Abd al-Muttalib, one of the youngest uncles of Muhammad and of the same Banu Hashim clan.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] This family relation to Muhammad made them appealing to those who were discontented with the rule of the Umayyad caliphs (661–750), who did not descend from the same family.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Over the course of their rule, the Umayyads even suppressed several rebellions that attempted to bring other members of Muhammad's family to power.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] One of the claims that the Abbasids made in the early years of their political movement was that Abu Hashim, the son of Muhammad ibn al-Hanafiyya and grandson of Ali, had formally transferred the Imamate (*imāmah*) to Muhammad ibn Ali (the great-grandson of Abbas) and thus to the Abbasid family.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Muhammad ibn Ali began to campaign in Persia for the return of power to the family of Muhammad, the Hashemites, in the context of the reign of Umar II.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Later, after they had attained power and needed to broaden their support among Muslims, the Abbasids supplemented this claim with other claims to justify their legitimacy.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Abbasids also distinguished themselves from the Umayyads by attacking their moral character and administration in general.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Abbasids also appealed to non-Arab Muslims, known as *mawali*, who remained outside the kinship-based society of the Arabs and were perceived as a lower class within the Umayyad empire.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] According to Ira Lapidus, "The Abbasid revolt was supported largely by Arabs, mainly the aggrieved settlers of Merv with the addition of the Yemeni faction and their Mawali".
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] During the reign of Marwan II, this opposition culminated in the rebellion of Ibrahim al-Imam, the fourth in descent from Abbas.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Supported by the province of Khurasan (eastern Iran), even though the governor opposed them, and the Shi'i Arabs, he achieved considerable success, but was captured and died in prison in 749.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] On 9 June 747 (15 Ramadan AH 129), Abu Muslim, rising from Khurasan, successfully initiated an open revolt against Umayyad rule, which was carried out under the sign of the Black Standard.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Close to 10,000 soldiers were under Abu Muslim's command when the hostilities officially began in Merv.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] General Qahtaba followed the fleeing governor Nasr ibn Sayyar west defeating the Umayyads at the Battle of Gorgan, the Battle of Nahavand and finally in the Battle of Karbala, all in the year 748.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Ibrahim was captured by Marwan and was killed.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The quarrel was taken up by Ibrahim's brother Abdallah, known by the name of Abu al-'Abbas al-Saffah, who defeated the Umayyads in 750 in the battle near the Great Zab river and was subsequently proclaimed caliph.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] After this loss, Marwan fled to Egypt, where he was subsequently killed.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The remainder of his family, barring one male, were also eliminated.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] 750–754) was spent consolidating Abbasid rule over the Muslim community.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Soon after the victory of 750, Abu Muslim sent forces to Central Asia to confront an army from Tang China led by Gao Xianzhi.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Gao Xianzhi and his army were defeated in 751 at the Battle of Talas, near present-day Tashkent, by the Abbasid army under Ziyad ibn Salih.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] This defeat marked the end of Tang influence in Transoxiana and halted Tang westward expansion.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Abbasids then consolidated their rule in Transoxania.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Elsewhere, the Abbasids focused on putting down numerous rebellions in Syria and Iraq.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Byzantines conducted raids during these early distractions.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] One of the first major changes effected by Abbasid rule was the move of the caliphate's center of power from Syria to Iraq.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] This was closer to the Persian *mawali* support base of the Abbasids and the move addressed their demand for reduced Arab dominance in the empire.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] However, no definitive capital was yet selected.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In these early Abbasid years, Kufa generally served as the administrative capital, but the caliphs were wary of the Alid sympathies in the city and did not always reside here.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In 752, al-Saffah built a new city called al-Hashimiyya, at an uncertain location, most likely near Kufa.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Later that same year, he moved to Anbar, where he built a new settlement for his Khurasani soldiers and a palace for himself.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] It was al-Saffah's successor, Abu Ja'far al-Mansur (r.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] 754–775) who firmly consolidated Abbasid rule and faced down internal challenges.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] His uncle, Abdallah ibn Ali, the victor over the Umayyads at the Battle of the Zab, was the most serious potential rival for leadership and al-Mansur sent Abu Muslim, the Khurasani revolutionary commander, against him in 754.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] After Abu Muslim successfully defeated him, al-Mansur then turned to eliminate Abu Muslim himself.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] He arranged to have him arrested and executed in 755.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] On the western frontier, the Abbasids were unable to re-assert caliphal control over the western and central Maghreb, which the Umayyads had lost in the 740s.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] One member of the Umayyad dynasty, Abd ar-Rahman, also managed to escape the purge of his family and established independent rule in al-Andalus (present-day Spain and Portugal) in 756, founding the Umayyad emirate of Córdoba.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In 756, al-Mansur had also sent over 4,000 Arab mercenaries to assist the Tang dynasty against the rebel leader An Lushan.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Abbasids, or "Black Flags" as they were commonly called, were known in Tang dynasty chronicles as the *hēiyī Dàshí*, "The Black-robed Tazi" (黑衣大食) ("Tazi" being a borrowing from Persian *Tāzī*, the word for "Arab").
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Later, Caliph Harun al-Rashid sent embassies to China and established good relations with the Tang emperors.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] After the war, these embassies remained in China and al-Rashid established an alliance with China.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Several embassies from the Abbasid caliphs to the Chinese court have been recorded in the *Old Book of Tang*, the most important being those of al-Saffah, al-Mansur, and Harun al-Rashid.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In 762, al-Mansur suppressed a rebellion in the Hejaz led by al-Nafs al-Zakiyya, a descendant from Ali ibn Abi Talib, whose challenge to the Abbasid claim to leadership was based on his Alid lineage and thus presented a serious political threat.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] He was defeated by an Abbasid army led by Isa ibn Musa.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] It was after this victory, in 762, that al-Mansur finally established a proper Abbasid capital, Baghdad – officially called *Madinat al-Salam* ('City of Peace') – located on the Tigris River, near the former ancient capital city of Ctesiphon.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Prior to this, he had continued to consider multiple sites for a capital, including al-Hashimiyya, which he used as a capital for a while, and al-Rumiyya (near the ruins of Ctesiphon), which he used for a few months.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Various other sites in the region also appear to have served as "capitals" under either al-Saffah or al-Mansur prior to the founding of Baghdad.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Al-Mansur centralised the judicial administration and, later, Harun al-Rashid established the institution of Great Qadi to oversee it.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Umayyad empire was mostly Arab; however, the Abbasids progressively became made up of more and more converted Muslims in which the Arabs were only one of many ethnicities.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Abbasids had depended heavily on the support of Persians in their overthrow of the Umayyads.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Al-Mansur welcomed non-Arab Muslims to his court.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] While this helped integrate Arab and Persian cultures, it alienated many of their Arab supporters, particularly the Khurasani Arabs who had supported them in their battles against the Umayyads.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] It was also during this early period of the dynasty, in particular during the rule of al-Mansur, Harun al-Rashid, and al-Ma'mun, that its reputation and power were created.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The position of *wazir* (vizier) developed in this period.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] It was initially akin to a secretary, but under the tenure of the Barmakids, an Iranian family close to the Abbasids, the position became powerful and Harun al-Rashid delegated state affairs to them for many years.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] This resulted in a more ceremonial role for many Abbasid caliphs compared with caliphal rule under the Umayyads; the viziers began to exert greater influence, and the role of the caliph's aristocracy was slowly replaced by a Barmakid bureaucracy.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] At the western end of the empire, Harun al-Rashid agreed to grant the province of Ifriqiya (centered in present-day Tunisia) as a hereditary emirate to Ibrahim ibn al-Aghlab, who founded the Aghlabid dynasty there.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] 786–809), the Abbasid Empire reached its peak.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] 775–785), restarted the fighting with the Byzantines, and his sons continued the conflict until Empress Irene pushed for peace.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] After several years of peace, Nikephoros I broke the treaty, then fended off multiple incursions during the first decade of the 9th century.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] These Abbasid attacks pushed into the Taurus Mountains, culminating with a victory at the Battle of Krasos and the massive invasion of 806, led by al-Rashid himself.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Harun al-Rashid's navy also proved successful, taking Cyprus.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Al-Rashid then focused on the rebellion of Rafi ibn al-Layth in Khurasan and died while there.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Domestically, al-Rashid pursued policies similar to those of his father al-Mahdi.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] He released many of the Umayyads and Alids his brother al-Hadi (r.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] 785–786) had imprisoned and declared amnesty for all political groups of the Quraysh.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] While Baghdad remained the official capital, al-Rashid chose to reside in Raqqa from 796 until the end of his reign.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In 802, he established an unusual succession plan which decreed that his son al-Amin would inherit the title of Caliph and have control of Iraq and the western empire while his other son al-Ma'mun would rule Khurasan and most eastern parts of the empire.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In 803, he turned on and imprisoned or killed most of the Barmakids, who had wielded administrative power on his behalf.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The reasons for this sudden and ruthless move remain unclear and have been the subject of much discussion by contemporary writers and later historians.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Al-Rashid's decision to split the succession proved to be damaging to the longevity of the empire.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] After his death in 809, his succession pact eventually collapsed and the empire was split by a civil war between al-Amin in Iraq and al-Ma'mun in Khurasan.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] This ended with a successful siege of Baghdad by al-Ma'mun's forces.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] When the city fell in 813, al-Amin was captured and executed on the orders of al-Ma'mun's general, Tahir ibn Husayn.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] This marked the first time that an Abbasid ruler was publicly executed and it irrevocably damaged the prestige of the caliphate.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Al-Ma'mun became caliph and ruled until his death in 833.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] He initially ruled the empire from his established base in Merv, Khurasan, where his main support was found, but this prolonged the discontent and instability in Iraq and triggered further fighting in the years following his victory.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In 817, he officially declared an Alid, 'Ali al-Rida, as his heir, instead of an Abbasid family member, perhaps hoping to promote Muslim unity, but the move backfired.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Eventually, he was compelled to step back from these policies and move his court to Baghdad, where he arrived in August 819.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] After this, the rest of his reign was relatively peaceful.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Exceptions included a rebellion in Azerbaijan by the Khurramites, supported by the Byzantines, which continued until 837.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] He also repulsed a Byzantine attack on Syria around 829, followed by counter-attacks into Anatolia, and suppressed a rebellion in Egypt in 832.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The later years of al-Ma'mun's reign are known for his intellectual interests and patronage.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The so-called "translation movement" — the state-sponsored translation of scientific and literary works of antiquity into Arabic — that had begun under his predecessors was pushed even further during this time and al-Ma'mun shifted its focus to ancient Greek works of science and philosophy.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In matters of religion, his interest in philosophy spurred him to endorse Mu'tazilism, the rationalist school of Islamic thought.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Under its influence, he officially endorsed the doctrine of createdness of the Qur'an in 827.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In 833, he went further and forcibly imposed it on the *ulama*, the Sunni religious scholars.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] This controversial policy, known as the *Mihna*, was eventually abandoned in 848.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Ultimately, it failed to convince the Sunni *ulama* and instead contributed to the emergence of the latter as a more cohesive social class whose views and interests did not always align with the caliph.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Following the civil war between al-Amin and al-Ma'mun, the traditional mainstay of the Abbasid army, the *Khurasaniyya* and *'Abna al-dawla*, were no longer seen as reliable and the caliphs sought to recruit a new type of army whose loyalty could be better assured.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] This process began under al-Ma'mun but it is his brother and successor, al-Mu'tasim (r.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] 833–842), who is known for its more radical implementation.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Soldiers were recruited from several new sources, but the most important, especially under al-Mu'tasim, were the group referred to by Arabic chronicles as "Turks" (*atrāk*), who appear to have been mainly Turkic people from Central Asia.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Some modern scholars refer to them as Mamluks, marking them as the antecedent of the later slave-soldiers known by that term, but their exact legal status has been a subject of scholarly debate.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Many, perhaps the majority, were originally purchased or captured slaves, but they were paid regular salaries and thus likely manumitted.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In any case, these outsiders did not have political ties among the traditional elites and thus their loyalty was to the caliph alone.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] These troops were likely the first standing army of the caliphate and provided the caliph with a strong base of military support.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] However, the influx of new foreign troops into the capital created tensions with its inhabitants and with older elites.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] This was one of the main reasons why, in 836, al-Mu'tasim decided to found a new capital, Samarra, on an open site to the north of Baghdad.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The new capital housed the caliph's army, allowed for the unhindered construction of massive new palaces, and became the focus of an even more elaborate courtly culture.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Al-Mu'tasim's reign marked the end of the strong caliphs.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] He strengthened his personal army with the Mamluks and promptly restarted the war with the Byzantines.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Though his attempt to seize Constantinople failed when his fleet was destroyed by a storm, his military excursions were generally successful, culminating with a resounding victory in the Sack of Amorium.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] From the ninth century onward, the Abbasids found they could no longer keep together a centralized polity from Baghdad, which had grown larger than that of Rome.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] As mentioned, Harun al-Rashid had already granted the province of Ifriqiya to the Aghlabids, who ruled this region as an autonomous vassal state until its fall to the Fatimids in 909.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In al-Ma'mun's reign, Tahir ibn Husayn (al-Ma'mun's general in the civil war) was appointed viceroy of Iran and most of the eastern regions of the empire from 821 onward.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] His descendants, the Tahirids, continued to govern in this position with significant autonomy until 873, although they remained loyal to the caliph and used only the title of *amir*.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] From their capital at Nishapur, they were important patrons of Arabic literature and Sunni religious scholarship, in addition to making major improvements to agriculture.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In Transoxiana, the Persian Samanids of Bukhara and Samarkand ruled as local governors, initially under the Tahirids.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] They oversaw the development of the region's cities into major trade centers, profiting from long-distance trade between China, Central Asia, Eastern Europe, and the Middle East.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] 847–861) was characterized by the caliph's extravagant spending, his attempts to further consolidate power within the state, and his replacement of the *Mihna* policy with support for more orthodox Sunni scholars, in particular the Hanbali school.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In 853, the Byzantines sacked Damietta in Egypt, and the caliph responded by sending troops into Anatolia, who sacked and marauded until they were eventually annihilated in 863.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Al-Mutawakkil's lifestyle and spending weakened his support among the military.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In 861, he was murdered at a party by a group of Turkish soldiers.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] This was the first time the Abbasid military intervened so directly and violently at court and it set a precedent for further coups.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The following period, sometimes known as the "Anarchy at Samarra" (861–870), saw four different caliphs come and go.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] While they each attempted to reassert their authority, they were at the mercy of military and political factions.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Tax collection lapsed and, along with al-Mutawakkil's previous spending, this left the state short on funds, which exacerbated the infighting.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In 865, the Turkish soldiers of Samarra even besieged Baghdad to overthrow the caliph al-Musta'in and, when the city fell the following year, they replaced him with al-Mu'tazz.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The latter was overthrown by the same faction in 869 and replaced by al-Muhtadi, who was similarly overthrown in 870.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Al-Muhtadi was succeeded by al-Mu'tamid, who was finally able to restore some order, in large part thanks to the help of his brother al-Muwaffaq, who kept the military under control and ran most government affairs.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The restoration was hampered by the Zanj rebellion, which erupted in 869 and threatened the center of Abbasid control in Iraq.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] This major threat was not brought under control until a determined campaign was launched in 879.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] By the 870s, Egypt became autonomous under Ahmad ibn Tulun and his Tulunid successors, though they continued to acknowledge the caliph and generally sent tribute to Baghdad.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] For a time, they even controlled Syria and parts of the Jazira (Upper Mesopotamia).
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In 882, the caliph al-Mu'tamid even tried to move his residence to Egypt at Ibn Tulun's invitation, though this move was aborted by the intervention of al-Muwaffaq.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In the east, the Saffarids were former soldiers in the Abbasid army who were stationed in Sistan and remained there as local strongmen.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] They began to challenge the Tahirids from 854 onward and in 873 they captured Nishapur, ending Tahirid rule.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] They marched on Baghdad in 876 but were defeated by al-Muwaffaq.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The two sides were forced to come to terms and the Abbasids allowed the Saffarids to rule over Sistan, Fars, Kirman, and Khurasan.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In 898, al-Mu'tadid set the Saffarids and Samanids against each other by formally endorsing a Saffarid claim over Transoxiana, the Samanid domain.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Samanids emerged triumphant in battle and were able to expand their control thenceforth to Khurasan, while the Saffarids were contained further south.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Samanids never threatened Iraq or western Iran, but they were also not as close to the caliphs as their Tahirid predecessors and in practice they were almost entirely independent of Baghdad.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] They became even greater patrons of religion and the arts than the Tahirids.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] They still maintained an orthodox Sunni ideology but they differed from their predecessors by promoting the Persian language.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] There was a brief Abbasid political and military revival at the end of the 9th century, especially under the policies of caliphs al-Mu'tadid (r.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Under al-Mu'tadid, the capital was moved from Samarra back to Baghdad.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Incursions by the Qarmatians and allied Bedouin tribes posed a serious threat from 899 onwards, but the Abbasid army, led by Muhammad ibn Sulayman, won a reprieve against them in 904 and 907.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In 905, the same general invaded Egypt and overthrew the weakened Tulunids, re-establishing Abbasid control to the west.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] By the time caliph al-Muktafi died in 908, the Abbasid revival was at its peak and a strong centralized state was in place again.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] After his death, however, the state became dominated by feuding bureaucrats.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] 908–932), the Abbasid court continued to project power and wealth publicly but the politics and financial policies of the time compromised the caliphate's sustainability in the long-term.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] It was in this period that the practice of giving out *iqta*s (fiefs in the form of tax farms) as favours began, which had the effect of reducing the caliphate's own tax revenues.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In 909, North Africa was lost to the Fatimid dynasty, an Isma'ili Shia sect tracing its roots to Muhammad's daughter Fatima.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Fatimids took control of Ifriqiya from the Aghlabids and eventually conquered Egypt in 969, where they established their capital, Cairo, near Fustat.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] By the end of the century, they were one of the main political and ideological challenges to Sunni Islam and the Abbasids, contesting the Abbasids for the titular authority of the Islamic *ummah*.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The challenge of the Fatimid Caliphate only ended with their downfall in the 12th century.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] 934–941), Baghdad's authority declined further as local governors refused to send payments to the capital.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Ikhshidids ruled Egypt and Syria autonomously prior to the Fatimid takeover.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Even in Iraq, many governors refused to obey and the caliph was unable to send armies against them.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Al-Radi was forced to invite the governor of Wasit, Muhammad ibn Ra'iq, to take over the administration under the newly created position of *amir al-umara* ("Commander of Commanders").
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Ibn Ra'iq disbanded the salaried army of the caliph and reduced much of the government's bureaucratic infrastructure, including the traditional vizierate, thus removing much of the Abbasid state's basis for power.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] He was overthrown in 938 and the following years were bogged down in political turmoil.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Al-Mustakfi had a short reign from 944 to 946, and it was during this period that the Persian faction known as the Buyids from Daylam swept into power and assumed control over the bureaucracy in Baghdad.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] According to the history of Miskawayh, they began distributing *iqta*s to their supporters.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] This period of localized secular control was to last nearly 100 years.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Mahmud of Ghazni took the title of sultan, as opposed to the *amir* that had been in more common usage, signifying the Ghaznavid Empire's independence from caliphal authority, despite Mahmud's ostentatious displays of Sunni orthodoxy and ritual submission to the caliph.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In the 11th century, the loss of respect for the caliphs continued, as some Islamic rulers no longer mentioned the caliph's name in the Friday *khutba*, or struck it off their coinage.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Despite the power of the Buyid amirs, the Abbasids retained a highly ritualized court in Baghdad, as described by the Buyid bureaucrat Hilal al-Sabi', and they retained a certain influence over Baghdad as well as religious life.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] As Buyid power waned with the rule of Baha' al-Daula, the caliphate was able to regain some measure of strength.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The caliph al-Qadir, for example, led the ideological struggle against the Shia with writings such as the *Baghdad Manifesto*.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The caliphs kept order in Baghdad itself, attempting to prevent the outbreak of *fitna*s in the capital, often contending with the *ayyarun*.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] With the Buyid dynasty on the wane, a vacuum was created that was eventually filled by the dynasty of Oghuz Turks known as the Seljuqs.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] By 1055, the Seljuqs had wrested control from the Buyids and Abbasids, and took temporal power.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] When the amir and former slave Basasiri took up the Shia Fatimid banner in Baghdad in 1056–57, the caliph al-Qa'im was unable to defeat him without outside help.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Toghril Beg, the Seljuq sultan, restored Baghdad to Sunni rule and took Iraq for his dynasty.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Once again, the Abbasids were forced to deal with a military power that they could not match, though the Abbasid caliph remained the titular head of the Islamic community.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The succeeding sultans Alp Arslan and Malikshah, as well as their vizier Nizam al-Mulk, took up residence in Persia, but held power over the Abbasids in Baghdad.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] When the dynasty began to weaken in the 12th century, the Abbasids gained greater independence once again.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] 1118–1135) was the first caliph to build an army and to lead it in battle since the 10th century.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] He recruited Kurdish and Arab Bedouin tribes and re-fortified Baghdad.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] His first concern was not the Seljuks but the Mazyadids of Hilla in central Iraq, whom he met in battle in 1123.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] His bid for independence was ultimately unsuccessful, as he was defeated by a Seljuk army in 1135 and assassinated soon after.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] 1136–1160), a new caliphal state began to emerge with the help of his vizier Ibn Hubayra.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Ibn Hubayra concentrated on reasserting authority in Iraq while the Seljuk Empire deteriorated.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Abbasids successfully defended Baghdad against the Seljuqs in the siege of 1157 and then conquered their Mazyadid enemies in Hilla in 1162.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] By the end of al-Muqtafi's reign, Baghdad controlled a state stretching from Basra in the south to the edges of Mosul in the north.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] After over two hundred years of Abbasid subjection to foreign dynasties, Caliph al-Mustanjid (r.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] 1160–1170) formally declared independence from the Seljuk sultans in 1165, when he dropped their names from Abbasid coinage.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Initially, the caliphs were still vulnerable to the power of the viziers, but al-Mustadi (r.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] 1170–1180) was able to further rally some support from the Baghdad public as well as symbolic support abroad from the Ayyubid sultan Saladin and the Rum Seljuk sultan Kilij Arslan II.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] 1180–1225) marked a definitive shift in late Abbasid power.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] He reinvigorated public displays of caliphal prestige, removed officials who were too powerful, engaged in diplomacy with regions beyond Iraq, and extended his control over former Seljuk territories in western Iran — including Isfahan, Hamadan, Qazvin and Zanjan.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] He sought to build up his influence among Muslim rulers abroad largely through the Sufi-inspired *futuwwa* brotherhood that he headed.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] 1226–1242), the Abbasid state achieved significant stability and many of the same policies continued.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] He built the Mustansiriyya Madrasa, inaugurated in 1234, the first madrasa to teach all four Sunni *maddhab*s (schools of jurisprudence) and the first madrasa commissioned by an Abbasid caliph.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In 1206, Genghis Khan established a powerful dynasty among the Mongols of Central Asia.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] During the 13th century, this Mongol Empire conquered most of the Eurasian land mass, including both China in the east and much of the old Islamic caliphate and the Kievan Rus' in the west.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In 1252, Hulagu Khan, a grandson of Genghis Khan and brother of the new Mongol ruler, Möngke Khan, was placed in charge of a new western campaign to the Middle East that would culminate in the conquest of Baghdad in 1258.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In the years leading up the Mongol invasion, Baghdad's strength was sapped by political rivalries, sectarian tensions between Sunnis and Shias, and damaging floods.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In 1257, after destroying the Assassins in Iran, Hulagu wrote to the Abbasid caliph, al-Musta'sim, demanding his submission.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The caliph refused, with Hulagu's status as a non-Muslim (unlike the earlier Buyids and Seljuks) likely a factor.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] There followed months of diplomacy, during which the Mongols may have been informed of Baghdad's weakness by correspondence with the caliph's vizier, Ibn al-Alqami, a Shia who was later accused of colluding with them.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Mongols began their siege of the city on 29 January 1258.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] On 10 February, al-Musta'sim agreed to meet with Hulagu, who demanded that the caliph order the defenders to stand down and come out of the city in exchange for mercy.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The caliph complied, but the Mongols slaughtered the population and then began the sack of the city on 13 February.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Contemporary accounts describe destruction, looting, rape, and killing on a massive scale over many days, with hundreds of thousands killed and the city reduced to near-empty ruins, though some, like the Christian and Shia communities, were spared.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Mongols feared rumours that a supernatural disaster would strike if the blood of al-Musta'sim, a direct descendant of Muhammad's uncle and part of a dynasty that had reigned for five centuries, was spilled.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] As a precaution and in accordance with a Mongol taboo against spilling royal blood, Hulagu had al-Musta'sim wrapped in a carpet and trampled to death by horses on 20 February 1258.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The caliph's immediate family was also executed, with the lone exceptions of his youngest son who was sent to Mongolia and a daughter who became a slave in the harem of Hulagu.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The fall of Baghdad marked the effective end of the Abbasid Caliphate.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] It made a deep impression on contemporary and later writers both inside and outside the Muslim world, some of whom created legendary stories about the last caliph's demise.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] It is also traditionally seen as the approximate end to the "classical age" or "golden age" of Islamic civilization.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The events brought profound geopolitical changes to the traditional lands of the Islamic caliphate, with Iraq, Iran, and most of the eastern lands falling under Mongol control while other Muslim rulers retained the lands to the west.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Mongol expansion further west was eventually halted by the Mamluks of Egypt at the Battle of Ain Jalut in 1260, followed by the conflict between the Ilkhanids (Hulagu and his successors) and their Golden Horde rivals, which diverted Mongol attention.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Prior to the Mongol invasion, the later Ayyubid sultans of Egypt had built up an army recruited from slaves, the Mamluks.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] During a political and military crisis in 1250, the Mamluks seized power and established what is now known as the Mamluk Sultanate.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Following the devastation of Baghdad in 1258 and in an effort to secure political legitimacy for the new regime in Egypt, the Mamluk ruler Baybars invited a surviving member of the Abbasid family to establish himself in Cairo in 1260–1261.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The new caliph was al-Mustansir II, a brother of the former caliph al-Mustansir.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In 1262, he disappeared while leading a small army in an attempt to recapture Baghdad from the Mongols.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Baybars subsequently replaced him with al-Hakim I, another Abbasid family member who had just been proclaimed in Aleppo.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Thereafter, the Abbasid caliphs in Cairo continued to exist as a strictly ceremonial but nonetheless important institution within the Mamluk Sultanate, conferring significant prestige on the Mamluks.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] It continued to be relevant even to other Muslim rulers until the 14th century; for example, the sultans of Delhi, the Muzaffarid sultan Muhammad, the Jalayirid sultan Ahmad, and the Ottoman sultan Bayezid I all sought diplomas of investiture from the caliph or declared nominal allegiance to him.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Caliph al-Musta'in even managed to reign as sultan in Cairo for a brief six months in 1412.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] During the 15th century, however, the institution of the caliph declined in significance.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The last Abbasid caliph in Cairo was al-Mutawakkil III, who was in place when the Ottoman sultan Selim I defeated the Mamluks in 1516 and conquered Egypt in 1517, ending the Mamluk Sultanate.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Selim I met with al-Mutawakkil III in Aleppo in 1516, prior to marching into Egypt, and the caliph was then sent to the Ottoman capital of Constantinople (present-day Istanbul), ending the Abbasid caliphate definitively.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Abbasids themselves slipped into historical obscurity after this.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The idea of a "caliphate" subsequently became an ambiguous concept that was occasionally revisited by later Muslim rulers and intellectuals for political or religious reasons.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Ottoman sultans, who were thenceforth the most powerful Muslim rulers in western Asia and the Mediterranean, did not use the title of "caliph" at all before the mid-16th century and only did so vaguely and inconsistently afterwards.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The claim that al-Mutawakkil III "transferred" the office of the caliph to the Ottoman sultan during their meeting in Aleppo is a legend that was elaborated in the 19th century and is not corroborated by contemporary accounts.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Abbasid historical period lasting to the Mongol conquest of Baghdad in 1258 CE is considered the Islamic Golden Age.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Islamic Golden Age was inaugurated by the middle of the 8th century by the ascension of the Abbasid Caliphate and the transfer of the capital from Damascus to Baghdad.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Abbasids were influenced by the Qur'anic injunctions and hadith, such as "the ink of a scholar is more holy than the blood of a martyr", stressing the value of knowledge.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Many classic works of antiquity that would otherwise have been lost were translated into Arabic and Persian and later in turn translated into Turkish, Hebrew and Latin.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] During this period the Muslim world was a cauldron of cultures which collected, synthesized and significantly advanced the knowledge gained from the Roman, Chinese, Indian, Persian, Egyptian, North African, Ancient Greek and Medieval Greek civilizations.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Abbasid literary culture in Iraq reflects long-term Mesopotamian narrative continuities, particularly traditions centered on heroic figures and on barriers separating chaos and order.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Core motifs associated with the Epic of Gilgamesh, mediated through the Alexander Romance, including journeys to the world's limits and the containment of chaos, persisted across religious and political change and continued to circulate in late antique Iraq.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Babylonian Talmud, composed by Iraq-based rabbis, preserves parallel traditions concerning Gog and Magog and the imagined edges of the world that confine agents of chaos.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Together, these traditions situate elements of Abbasid literature within a Mesopotamian narrative continuum.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The best-known fiction from the Islamic world is *One Thousand and One Nights*, a collection of fantastical folk tales, legends and parables compiled primarily during the Abbasid era.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The collection is recorded as having originated from an Arabic translation of a Sassanian-era Persian prototype, with likely origins in Indian literary traditions.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Stories from Arabic, Persian, Mesopotamian, and Egyptian folklore and literature were later incorporated.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The epic is believed to have taken shape in the 10th century and reached its final form by the 14th century; the number and type of tales have varied from one manuscript to another.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] All Arabian fantasy tales were often called "Arabian Nights" when translated into English, regardless of whether they appeared in *The Book of One Thousand and One Nights*.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] This epic has been influential in the West since it was translated in the 18th century, first by Antoine Galland.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Many imitations were written, especially in France.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Various characters from this epic have themselves become cultural icons in Western culture, such as Aladdin, Sinbad and Ali Baba.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] A famous example of Islamic poetry on romance was *Layla and Majnun*, an originally Arabic story which was further developed by Iranian, Azerbaijani and other poets in the Persian, Azerbaijani, and Turkish languages.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] It is a tragic story of undying love much like the later *Romeo and Juliet*.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Arabic poetry reached its greatest height in the Abbasid era, especially before the loss of central authority and the rise of the Persianate dynasties.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Writers like Abu Tammam and Abu Nuwas were closely connected to the caliphal court in Baghdad during the early 9th century, while others such as al-Mutanabbi received their patronage from regional courts.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Under Harun al-Rashid, Baghdad was renowned for its bookstores, which proliferated after the making of paper was introduced.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Chinese papermakers had been among those taken prisoner by the Arabs at the Battle of Talas in 751.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] As prisoners of war, they were dispatched to Samarkand, where they helped set up the first Arab paper mill.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In time, paper replaced parchment as the medium for writing, and the production of books greatly increased.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] These events had an academic and societal impact that could be broadly compared to the introduction of the printing press in the West.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Paper aided in communication and record-keeping, it also brought a new sophistication and complexity to businesses, banking, and the civil service.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In 794, Jafa al-Barmak built the first paper mill in Baghdad, and from there the technology circulated.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Harun required that paper be employed in government dealings, since something recorded on paper could not easily be changed or removed, and eventually, an entire street in Baghdad's business district was dedicated to selling paper and books.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] One of the common definitions for "Islamic philosophy" is "the style of philosophy produced within the framework of Islamic culture".
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Islamic philosophy, in this definition is neither necessarily concerned with religious issues, nor is exclusively produced by Muslims.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Their works on Aristotle were a key step in the transmission of learning from ancient Greeks to the Islamic world and the West.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] They often corrected the philosopher, encouraging a lively debate in the spirit of ijtihad.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] They also wrote influential original philosophical works, and their thinking was incorporated into Christian philosophy during the Middle Ages, notably by Thomas Aquinas.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Three speculative thinkers, al-Kindi, al-Farabi, and Avicenna, combined Aristotelianism and Neoplatonism with other ideas introduced through Islam, and Avicennism was later established as a result.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Other influential Abbasid philosophers include al-Jahiz, and Ibn al-Haytham (Alhacen).
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] As power shifted from the Umayyads to the Abbasids, the architectural styles changed also, from Greco-Roman tradition (which features elements of Hellenistic and Roman representative style) to Eastern tradition which retained their independent architectural traditions from Mesopotamia and Persia.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] A defining characteristic of Abbasid architecture in Iraq was the extensive use of stucco and plaster decoration, particularly in interior spaces.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The limited availability of high-quality building stone in Abbasid Iraq contributed to the widespread use of stucco and other malleable materials, which were well suited to repetitive and abstract ornamental decoration.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] At Samarra, these conditions enabled the emergence of a standardized decorative vocabulary that departed from Late Antique naturalism and proved influential well beyond Iraq.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Color also played an important role, particularly the use of blue pigments to enhance stucco and painted surfaces, intensifying abstraction and, in some contexts, carrying protective or apotropaic associations.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Abbasid architecture was particularly influenced by Sasanian architecture, which in turn featured elements present since ancient Mesopotamia.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The Christian styles evolved into a style based more on the Sasanian Empire, utilizing mud bricks and baked bricks with carved stucco.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Other architectural innovations and styles were few, such as the four-centered arch, and a dome erected on squinches.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Unfortunately, much was lost due to the ephemeral nature of the stucco and luster tiles.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Another major development was the creation or vast enlargement of cities as they were turned into the capital of the empire, beginning with the creation of Baghdad in 762, which was planned as a walled city with four gates, and a mosque and palace in the center.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Al-Mansur, who was responsible for the creation of Baghdad, also planned the city of Raqqa, along the Euphrates.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Finally, in 836, al-Mu'tasim moved the capital to a new site that he created along the Tigris, called Samarra.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] This city saw 60 years of work, with race-courses and game preserves to add to the atmosphere.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Due to the dry remote nature of the environment, some of the palaces built in this era were isolated havens.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Al-Ukhaidir Fortress is a fine example of this type of building, which has stables, living quarters, and a mosque, all surrounding inner courtyards.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Iraq only has one surviving mausoleum from this era, in Samarra: an octagonal domed structure known as the *Qubbat al-Sulaibiyya*, which is the first known monumental tomb in Islamic architecture and may be the final resting place of al-Muntasir.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Baghdad, the epicenter of the empire, was originally organized in a circular fashion next to the Tigris River, with massive brick walls being constructed in successive rings around the core by a workforce of 100,000 with four huge gates (named Kufa, Basra, Khurasan and Syria).
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The central enclosure of the city contained Mansur's palace of 360,000 square feet (33,000 m2) in area and the great mosque of Baghdad, encompassing 90,000 square feet (8,400 m2).
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Travel across the Tigris and the network of waterways allowing the drainage of the Euphrates into the Tigris was facilitated by bridges and canals servicing the population.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Outside the Abbasid heartlands, architecture was still influenced by the capital.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In present-day Tunisia, the Great Mosque of Kairouan was founded under the Umayyad dynasty but completely rebuilt in the 9th century under the patronage of the Aghlabids, vassals of the Abbasids.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The styles utilized were mainly Abbasid.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] In Egypt, Ahmad Ibn Tulun commissioned the Ibn Tulun Mosque, completed in 879, that is based on the style of Samarra and is now one of the best-preserved Abbasid-style mosques from this period.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The establishment of Abbasid power based in Iraq, rather than Syria, resulted in a cultural and artistic development influenced not only by the Mediterranean and Middle Eastern traditions but also by connections further afield with India, Central Asia, and China.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] The importation of Chinese ceramics elicited local imitations but also stirred innovations in local production.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Abbasid ceramics became a more important art form with greater emphasis on decoration.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] A major innovation was the emergence of monochrome and polychrome lustreware, a technical achievement that had an important impact on the wider development of Islamic ceramics.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Glassware also became a more important art form and was likely the origin of the lustre technique that was introduced into ceramics.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Few textiles have survived but the production of *tiraz*, textiles with royal inscriptions, is well attested.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Another major art form was calligraphy and manuscript production.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] During the Abbasid period, Arabic calligraphy evolved into a more refined discipline.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Rounded Kufic script was typical and became increasingly stylized.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Parchment only allowed for a few lines of script, but from the late 8th century onward paper began to be produced.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p01] Qur'ans are the main type of book to have survived from this period.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] A number of medieval thinkers and scientists living under Islamic rule played a role in transmitting Islamic science to the Christian West.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] In addition, the period saw the recovery of much of the Alexandrian mathematical, geometric and astronomical knowledge, such as that of Euclid and Claudius Ptolemy.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] These recovered mathematical methods were later enhanced and developed by other Islamic scholars, notably by Persian scientists Al-Biruni and Abu Nasr Mansur.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Christians (particularly Nestorian Christians) contributed to the Arab Islamic Civilization during the Umayyads and the Abbasids by translating works of Greek philosophers to Syriac and afterwards to Arabic.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Nestorians played a prominent role in the formation of Arab culture, with the Academy of Gondishapur being prominent in the late Sassanid, Umayyad and early Abbasid periods.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Notably, eight generations of the Nestorian Bukhtishu family served as private doctors to caliphs and sultans between the eighth and eleventh centuries.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Algebra was significantly developed by Persian scientist Muhammad ibn Mūsā al-Khwārizmī during this time in his landmark text, *Kitab al-Jabr wa-l-Muqabala*, from which the term *algebra* is derived.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] He is thus considered to be the father of algebra by some, although the Greek mathematician Diophantus has also been given this title.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The terms *algorism* and *algorithm* are derived from the name of al-Khwarizmi, who was also responsible for introducing the Arabic numerals and Hindu–Arabic numeral system beyond the Indian subcontinent.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Arab scientist Ibn al-Haytham (Alhazen) developed an early scientific method in his *Book of Optics* (1021).
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The most important development of the scientific method was the use of experiments to distinguish between competing scientific theories set within a generally empirical orientation, which began among Muslim scientists.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Ibn al-Haytham's empirical proof of the intromission theory of light (that is, that light rays entered the eyes rather than being emitted by them) was particularly important.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Ibn al-Haytham was significant in the history of scientific method, particularly in his approach to experimentation, and has been referred to as the "world's first true scientist".
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Medicine in medieval Islam was an area of science that advanced particularly during the Abbasids' reign.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] During the 9th century, Baghdad contained over 800 doctors, and great discoveries in the understanding of anatomy and diseases were made.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The clinical distinction between measles and smallpox was described during this time.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Famous Persian scientist Ibn Sina (known to the West as Avicenna) produced treatises and works that summarized the vast amount of knowledge that scientists had accumulated, and was very influential through his encyclopedias, *The Canon of Medicine* and *The Book of Healing*.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The work of him and many others directly influenced the research of European scientists during the Renaissance.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Astronomy in medieval Islam was advanced by Al-Battani, who improved the precision of the measurement of the precession of the Earth's axis.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The corrections made to the geocentric model by al-Battani, Averroes, Nasir al-Din al-Tusi, Mo'ayyeduddin Urdi and Ibn al-Shatir were later incorporated into the Copernican heliocentric model.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The astrolabe, though originally developed by the Greeks, was developed further by Islamic astronomers and engineers, and subsequently brought to medieval Europe.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Muslim alchemists influenced medieval European alchemists, particularly the writings attributed to Jābir ibn Hayyān (Geber).
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] In technology, the Abbasids adopted papermaking from China.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The use of paper spread from China into the caliphate in the 8th century CE, arriving in al-Andalus (Islamic Spain) and then the rest of Europe in the 10th century.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] It was easier to manufacture than parchment, less likely to crack than papyrus, and could absorb ink, making it ideal for making records and copies of the Qur'an.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] "Islamic paper makers devised assembly-line methods of hand-copying manuscripts to turn out editions far larger than any available in Europe for centuries." It was from the Abbasids that the rest of the world learned to make paper from linen.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The knowledge of gunpowder was also transmitted from China via the caliphate, where the formulas for pure potassium nitrate and an explosive gunpowder effect were first developed.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Advances were made in irrigation and farming, using new technology such as the windmill.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Crops such as almonds and citrus fruit were brought to Europe through al-Andalus, and sugar cultivation was gradually adopted by the Europeans.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Apart from the Nile, Tigris and Euphrates, navigable rivers were uncommon, so transport by sea was very important.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Navigational sciences were highly developed, making use of a rudimentary sextant (known as a *kamal*).
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] When combined with detailed maps of the period, sailors were able to sail across oceans rather than skirt along the coast.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Abbasid sailors were also responsible for reintroducing large three masted merchant vessels to the Mediterranean.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The name *caravel* may derive from an earlier Arab ship known as the *qārib*.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Arab merchants dominated trade in the Indian Ocean until the arrival of the Portuguese in the 16th century.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Hormuz was an important center for this trade.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] There was also a dense network of trade routes in the Mediterranean, along which Muslim countries traded with each other and with European powers such as Venice or Genoa.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The Silk Road crossing Central Asia passed through the Abbasid caliphate between China and Europe.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Engineers in the Abbasid caliphate made a number of innovative industrial uses of hydropower, and early industrial uses of tidal power, wind power, and petroleum (notably by distillation into kerosene).
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The industrial uses of watermills in the Islamic world date back to the 7th century, while horizontal-wheeled and vertical-wheeled water mills were both in widespread use since at least the 9th century.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] By the time of the Crusades, every province throughout the Islamic world had mills in operation, from al-Andalus and North Africa to the Middle East and Central Asia.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] These mills performed a variety of agricultural and industrial tasks.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Abbasid engineers also developed machines (such as pumps) incorporating crankshafts, employed gears in mills and water-raising machines, and used dams to provide additional power to watermills and water-raising machines.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Such advances made it possible for many industrial tasks that were previously driven by manual labour in ancient times to be mechanized and driven by machinery instead in the medieval Islamic world.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] It has been argued that the industrial use of waterpower had spread from Islamic to Christian Spain, where fulling mills, paper mills, and forge mills were recorded for the first time in Catalonia.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] A number of industries were generated during the Arab Agricultural Revolution, including early industries for textiles, sugar, rope-making, matting, silk, and paper.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Latin translations of the 12th century passed on knowledge of chemistry and instrument making in particular.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The agricultural and handicraft industries also experienced high levels of growth during this period.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] While the Abbasids originally gained power by exploiting the social inequalities against non-Arabs in the Umayyad Empire, during Abbasid rule the empire rapidly Arabized, particularly in the Fertile Crescent region (namely Mesopotamia and the Levant) as had begun under Umayyad rule.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] As knowledge was shared in the Arabic language throughout the empire, many people from different nationalities and religions began to speak Arabic in their everyday lives.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Resources from other languages began to be translated into Arabic, and a unique Islamic identity began to form that fused previous cultures with Arab culture, creating a level of civilization and knowledge that was considered a marvel in Europe at the time.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] In contrast to the earlier era, women in Abbasid society were absent from all arenas of the community's central affairs.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] While their Muslim forebears led men into battle, started rebellions, and played an active role in community life, as demonstrated in the Hadith literature, Abbasid women were ideally kept in seclusion.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Conquests had brought enormous wealth and large numbers of slaves to the Muslim elite.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The majority of the slaves were women and children, many of whom had been dependents or harem-members of the defeated Sassanian upper classes.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] In the wake of the conquests an elite man could potentially own a thousand slaves, and ordinary soldiers could have ten people serving them.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Even so, slave courtesans (qiyans and jawaris) and princesses produced prestigious and important poetry.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Enough survives to give us access to women's historical experiences, and reveals some vivacious and powerful figures, such as the Sufi mystic Raabi'a al-Adwiyya (714–801 CE), the princess and poet 'Ulayya bint al-Mahdi (777–825 CE), and the singing-girls Shāriyah (c.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Each wife in the Abbasid harem had an additional home or flat, with her own enslaved staff of eunuchs and maidservants.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] When a concubine gave birth to a son, she was elevated in rank to umm walad and also received apartments and (slave) servants as a gift.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The status and treatment of Jews, Christians, and non-Muslims in the Abbasid Caliphate was a complex and continually changing issue.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Dhimmis faced some level of discrimination in Abbasid society: they did not have all the privileges of Muslims and had to pay jizya, a tax on non-Muslims.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] However, as people of the book (non-Muslim monotheists), Jews and Christians were allowed to practice their religion and were not required to convert.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Ecclesiastical authorities discouraged practices such as polygamy and sought to regulate interreligious unions, yet ordinary Christians in Iraq and neighboring regions nonetheless participated in both Christian and Islamic marital practices and households across confessional lines.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Christian men might take multiple wives or marry non-Christians, and interreligious marriages, especially those involving Muslim husbands and Christian women, were a persistent concern for Christian jurists, who viewed them as threatening communal boundaries.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] One of the common aspects of the treatment of the dhimmis is that their treatment depended on who the caliph was at the time.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Some Abbasid rulers, like Al-Mutawakkil (822–861 CE) imposed strict restrictions on what dhimmis could wear in public, often yellow garments that distinguished them from Muslims.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Other restrictions al-Mutawakkil imposed included limiting the role of the dhimmis in government, seizing dhimmi housing and making it harder for dhimmis to become educated.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Most other Abbasid caliphs were not as strict as al-Mutawakkil.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] During the reign of Al-Mansur (754–775 CE), it was common for Jews and Christians to influence the overall culture in the caliphate, specifically in Baghdad.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Jews and Christians did this by participating in scholarly work.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] It was common that laws that were imposed against dhimmis during one caliph's rule were either discarded or not practiced during future caliphs' reigns.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Al-Mansur and al-Mutawakkil both instituted laws that forbade non-Muslims from participating in public office.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Al-Mansur did not follow his own law very closely, bringing dhimmis back to the caliphate's treasury due to the needed expertise of dhimmis in the area of finance.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Al-Mutawakkil followed the law banning dhimmis from public office more seriously, although, soon after his reign, many of the laws concerning dhimmis participating in government were completely unobserved or at least less strictly observed.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] 908–932 CE), who held a similar stance as al-Mutawakkil on barring non-Muslims from public office, himself had multiple Christian secretaries, indicating that non-Muslims still had access to many of the most important figures within the caliphate.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Past having a casual association or just being a secretary to high-ranking Islamic officials, some of them achieved the second highest office after the caliph: the vizier.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Jews and Christians may have had a lower overall status compared to Muslims in the Abbasid Caliphate, but dhimmis were often allowed to hold respectable and even prestigious occupations in some cases, such as doctors and public officeholders.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Jews and Christians were also allowed to be rich even if they were taxed for being a dhimmi.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Dhimmis were capable of moving up and down the social ladder, though this largely depended on the particular caliph.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] An indication as to the social standing of Jews and Christians at the time was their ability to live next to Muslim people.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] While al-Mansur was ruling the caliphate, for instance, it was not uncommon for dhimmis to live in the same neighborhoods as Muslims.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] One of the biggest reasons why dhimmis were allowed to hold prestigious jobs and positions in government is that they were generally important to the well-being of the state and were proficient to excellent with the work at hand.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] In general, Muslims, Jews, and Christians had close relations that could be considered positive at times, especially for Jews, in contrast to how Jews were being treated in Europe.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Many of the laws and restrictions that were imposed on dhimmis often resembled other laws that previous states had used to discriminate against a minority religion, specifically Jewish people.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Romans in the fourth century banned Jewish people from holding public offices, banned Roman citizens from converting to Judaism, and often demoted Jews who were serving in the Roman military.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] In direct contrast, there was an event in which two viziers, Ibn al-Furat and Ali ibn Isa ibn al-Jarrah, argued about Ibn al-Furat's decision to make a Christian the head of the military.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] A previous vizier, Abu Muhammad al-Hasan al-Bazuri, had done so.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] These laws predated al-Mansur's laws against dhimmis and often had similar restrictions, although Roman emperors were often much more strict on enforcing these laws than many Abbasid caliphs.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Most of Baghdad's Jews were incorporated into the Arab community and considered Arabic their native language.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Some Jews studied Hebrew in their schools and Jewish religious education flourished.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The united Muslim empire allowed Jews to reconstruct links between their dispersed communities throughout the Middle East.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The city's Talmudic institute helped spread the rabbinical tradition to Europe, and the Jewish community in Baghdad went on to establish ten rabbinical schools and twenty-three synagogues.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Baghdad not only contained the tombs of Muslim saints and martyrs, but also the tomb of Yusha, whose corpse had been brought to Iraq during the first migration of the Jews out of the Levant.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] There were large feasts on certain days, as the Muslims of the empire celebrated Christian holidays as well as their own.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] There were two main Islamic feasts: one marked by the end of Ramadan; the other, "the Feast of Sacrifice".
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The former was especially joyful because children would purchase decorations and sweetmeats; people prepared the best food and bought new clothes.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] At midmorning, the caliph, wearing Muhammad's thobe, would guide officials, accompanied by armed soldiers to the Great Mosque, where he led prayers.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] After the prayer, all those in attendance would exchange the best wishes and hug their kin and companions.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] During those limited number of nights, the palaces were lit up and boats on the Tigris hung lights.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] It was said that Baghdad "glittered 'like a bride'".
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] During the Feast of Sacrifice, sheep were butchered in public arenas and the caliph participated in a large-scale sacrifice in the palace courtyard.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Afterward, the meat would be divided and given to the poor.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] In addition to these two holidays, Shias celebrated the birthdays of Fatimah and Ali ibn Abi Talib.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Matrimonies and births in the royal family were observed by all in the empire.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The announcement that one of the caliph's sons could recite the Koran smoothly was greeted by communal jubilation.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] When Harun developed this holy talent, the people lit torches and decorated the streets with wreaths of flowers, and his father, Al-Mahdi, freed 500 slaves.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Of all the holidays imported from other cultures and religions, the one most celebrated in Baghdad (a city with many Persians) was Nowruz, which celebrated the arrival of spring.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] In a ceremonial ablution introduced by Persian troops, residents sprinkled themselves with water and ate almond cakes.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The palaces of the imperial family were lit up for six days and nights.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The Abbasids also celebrated the Persian holiday of Mihraj, which marked the onset of winter (signified with pounding drums), and Sadar, when homes burned incense and the masses would congregate along the Tigris to witness princes and viziers pass by.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The Abbasid army amassed an array of siege equipment, such as catapults, mangonels, battering rams, ladders, grappling irons, and hooks.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] All such weaponry was operated by military engineers.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] However, the primary siege weapon was the *manjaniq*, a type of siege weapon that was comparable to the trebuchet employed in Western medieval times.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] From the seventh century onward, it had largely replaced torsion artillery.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] By Harun al-Rashid's time, the Abbasid army employed fire grenades.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The Abbasids also utilized field hospitals and ambulances drawn by camels.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The cavalry was entirely covered in iron, with helmets.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Similar to medieval knights, their only exposed spots were the end of their noses and small openings in front of their eyes.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Their foot soldiers were issued spears, swords, and pikes, and (in line with Persian fashion) trained to stand so solidly that, one contemporary wrote "you would have thought them held fast by clamps of bronze".
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Although the Abbasids never retained a substantial regular army, the caliph could recruit a considerable number of soldiers in a short time when needed from levies.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] There were also cohorts of regular troops who received steady pay and a special forces unit.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] At any moment, 125,000 Muslim soldiers could be assembled along the Byzantine frontier, Baghdad, Medina, Damascus, Rayy, and other geostrategic locations in order to quell any unrest.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] During the Abbasid revolution, Abu Muslim's Khorasani army, composed largely of Arab settlers disillusioned with Umayyad rule, marched under black banners, forming a powerful force that swept westward in open revolt.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] In Baghdad there were many Abbasid military leaders who were or said they were of Arab descent.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] However, it is clear that most of the ranks were of Iranian origin, the vast majority being from Khurasan and Transoxiana, not from western Iran or Azerbaijan.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Most of the Khurasani soldiers who brought the Abbasids to power were Arabs.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The standing army of the Muslims in Khurasan was overwhelmingly Arab.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The unit organization of the Abbasids was designed with the goal of ethnic and racial equality among supporters.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] When Abu Muslim recruited officers along the Silk Road, he registered them based not on their tribal or ethno-national affiliations but on their current places of residence.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Under the Abbasids, Iranian peoples became better represented in the army and bureaucracy as compared to before.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] He abolished the old *jund* system created by Umar and diverted the salaries of the original Arab military descendants to the Turkic slave soldiers.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The Turkic soldiers transformed the style of warfare, as they were known as capable horse archers, trained from childhood to ride.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] This military was now drafted from the ethnic groups of the faraway borderlands, and were completely separate from the rest of society.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] This led to the decline of the caliphate starting with the Anarchy at Samarra.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] As a result of such a vast Empire, the caliphate was decentralized and divided into 24 provinces.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Harun's vizier enjoyed close to unchecked powers.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Under Harun, a special "bureau of confiscation" was created.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] This governmental wing made it possible for the vizier to seize the property and riches of any corrupt governor or civil servant.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] In addition, it allowed governors to confiscate the estates of lower-ranking officials.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Finally, the caliph could impose the same penalty on a vizier who fell from grace.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] As one later caliph put it: "The vizier is our representative throughout the land and amongst our subjects.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Every regional metropolis had a post office and hundreds of roads were paved in order to link the imperial capital with other cities and towns.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The empire employed a system of relays to deliver mail.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The central post office in Baghdad even had a map with directions that noted the distances between each town.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The roads were provided with roadside inns, hospices, and wells and could reach eastward through Persia and Central Asia, to as far as China.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The post office not only enhanced civil services but also served as intelligence for the caliph.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Mailmen were employed as spies who kept an eye on local affairs.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Early in the days of the caliphate, the Barmakids took the responsibility of shaping the civil service.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The family had roots in a Buddhist monastery in northern Afghanistan.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] In the early 8th century, the family converted to Islam and began to take on a sizable part of the civil administration for the Abbasids.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Capital poured into the caliphate's treasury from a variety of taxes, including a real estate tax; a levy on cattle, gold and silver, and commercial wares; a special tax on non-Muslims; and customs dues.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Under Harun al-Rashid, maritime trade through the Persian Gulf thrived, with Arab vessels trading as far south as Madagascar and as far east as China, Korea, and Japan.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The growing economy of Baghdad and other cities inevitably led to the demand for luxury items and formed a class of entrepreneurs who organized long-range caravans for the trade and then the distribution of their goods.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] A whole section in the East Baghdad suq was dedicated to Chinese goods.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Much of this direct maritime trade was oriented toward Iraqi markets, particularly Basra and Baghdad, which functioned as major destinations for goods arriving from Tang China.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] From the seventh to the tenth centuries, merchants from the Gulf served Iraqi markets through direct sea routes linking the Persian Gulf to the South China coast, especially Guangzhou, as attested by both contemporary textual sources and archaeological evidence.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The ninth-century Belitung shipwreck, carrying a large cargo of Chinese ceramics, illustrates the scale of this trade and its connection to demand in Iraq and the wider Abbasid realm.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Arabs traded with the Baltic region and made it as far north as the British Isles.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Tens of thousands of Arab coins have been discovered in parts of Russia and Sweden, which bear witness to the comprehensive trade networks set up by the Abbasids.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] King Offa of Mercia (in England) minted gold coins similar to those of the Abbasids in the eighth century.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Muslim merchants employed ports in Bandar Siraf, Basra, and Aden and some Red Sea ports to travel and trade with India and South East Asia.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Land routes were also utilized through Central Asia.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Arab businessmen were present in China as early as the eighth century.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Arab merchants sailed the Caspian Sea to reach and trade with Bukhara and Samarkand.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] During the ninth and tenth centuries, large quantities of opaque glazed pottery were produced in southern Iraq, within the heartlands of the Abbasid Caliphate, and exported as a mass-produced commercial commodity.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Finds of this Iraqi ware at sites across the Middle East, South Africa, and Southeast Asia demonstrate sustained commercial interaction between Iraq and the wider Indian Ocean world.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Most of the exported vessels were standardized and practical in design, indicating that they were produced for large-scale commercial trade rather than for elite or luxury use.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Many caravans and goods never made it to their intended destinations.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Some Chinese exports perished in fires, while other ships sank.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] It was said that anybody who made it to China and back unharmed was blessed by God.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Common sea routes were also plagued by pirates who built and crewed vessels that were faster than most merchant ships.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] It is said that many of the adventures at sea in the Sinbad tales were based on historical fiction of mariners of the day.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The Abbasids also established overland trade with Africa, largely for gold and slaves.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] When trade with Europe ceased due to hostilities, Jews served as a link between the two hostile worlds.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] The Abbasids engaged in extensive trade with the Italian maritime republics of Venice and Genoa, from the 11th century.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Venetian merchants facilitated the exchange of high-value goods such as spices, silk, and precious metals from the East.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] In return, Venice exported European manufactured goods and luxury items.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] While Genoese merchants traded in luxury goods like spices, textiles, and other high-demand items.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] Genoa's strategic position in the Mediterranean enabled it to integrate into the broader Mediterranean trade network, connecting the Abbasid Caliphate with other European markets.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] These trade relations played a key role in linking the medieval Mediterranean with the broader Islamic world.
[src:crusades/abbasids-p02] This exchange of goods, alongside cultural and technological transfers, fostered a more interconnected medieval global economy.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] In Christianity, **ablution** is a prescribed washing of part or all of the body or possessions, such as clothing or ceremonial objects, with the intent of purification or dedication.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] In Christianity, both baptism and footwashing are forms of ablution.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Before praying the canonical hours at seven fixed prayer times, Oriental Orthodox Christians wash their hands and face (cf.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] In liturgical churches, ablution can refer to purifying fingers or vessels related to the Eucharist.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] According to the Gospel of Matthew, Pontius Pilate declared himself innocent of the blood of Jesus by washing his hands.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] This act of Pilate may not, however, have been borrowed from the custom of the Jews.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The same practice was common among the Greeks and Romans.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] According to Christian tradition, the Pharisees carried the practice of ablution to great excess.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] In the Old Testament, ablution was considered a prerequisite to approaching God, whether by means of sacrifice, prayer, or entering a holy place.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Around the time of Tertullian, an early Church Father, it was customary for Christians to wash their hands (*manulavium*), head (*capitilavium*) and feet (*pedilavium*) before prayer, as well as before receiving Holy Communion.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The rite of footwashing employed a basin of water and linen towels, done in the imitation of Christ (as recorded by the early Christian apologist Tertullian).
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Churches from the time of Constantine the Great were thus built with an exonarthex that included a cantharus where Christians would wash their hands, face and feet before entering the worship space.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The Bible has many rituals of purification relating to menstruation, childbirth, sexual relations, nocturnal emission, unusual bodily fluids, skin disease, death, and animal sacrifices.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The Biblical rituals of purification ranging in areas from the mundane private rituals of personal hygiene and toilet etiquette to the complex public rituals of social etiquette.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] This is to show respect for the Bible and in the Middle East and in the Indian subcontinent, Christians place their copies of Scripture in a rehal to have it rest in an elevated position.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church prescribes several kinds of hand washing for example after leaving the latrine, lavatory or bathhouse, or before prayer, or after eating a meal.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The women in the Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church are prohibited from entering the church temple during menses; and the men do not enter a church the day after they have had intercourse with their wives.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Christianity has always placed a strong emphasis on hygiene.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The Church also built public bathing facilities that were separate for both sexes near monasteries and pilgrimage sites; also, the popes situated baths within church basilicas and monasteries since the early Middle Ages.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Pope Gregory the Great urged his followers on value of bathing as a bodily need.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Contrary to popular belief bathing and sanitation were not lost in Europe with the collapse of the Roman Empire.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Soapmaking first became an established trade during the so-called "Dark Ages".
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The Romans used scented oils (mostly from Egypt), among other alternatives.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] By the mid-19th century, the English urbanised middle classes had formed an ideology of cleanliness that ranked alongside typical Victorian concepts, such as Christianity, respectability and social progress.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The Salvation Army has adopted movement of the deployment of the personal hygiene, and by providing personal hygiene products.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Now in case the one having a running discharge would become clean from his running discharge, he must then count for himself seven days for his purification, and he must wash his garments and bathe his flesh in running water; and he must be clean.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The Mikveh in the Bible is a bath used for the purpose of ritual immersion.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The word is employed in its broader sense but generally means a collection of water.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Several biblical regulations specify that full immersion in water is required to regain ritual purity after ritually impure incidents have occurred.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] A person was required to be ritually pure in order to enter the Temple.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The churching of women is still performed in a number of Eastern Christian churches (Eastern Orthodox, Oriental Orthodox and Eastern Catholic churches).
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Oriental Orthodox Churches such as the Coptic Orthodox, Ethiopian Orthodox, Eritrean Orthodox, places a heavier emphasis on Old Testament teachings, and its followers adhere to certain practices such as observing days of ritual purification.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Before praying, they wash their hands and face in order to be clean before and present their best to God.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Roman Catholics, Eastern Orthodox, Lutherans and High church Anglicans are also traditionally required to regularly attend confession, as a form of ritual purification from sin, especially as preparation before receiving the Eucharist.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] For Catholics, this is required at least once a year and required for those who are guilty of unconfessed mortal sins.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] In Reformed tradition, ritual purity is achieved through the Confession of Sins, and Assurance of Forgiveness, and Sanctification.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Through the power of the Holy Spirit, believers offer their whole being and labor as a 'living sacrifice'; and cleanliness becomes a way of life (See Romans 12:1, and John 13:5–10 (the Washing of the Feet).
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] In Anabaptist Christianity (inclusive of Mennonites, Amish, Hutterites, Bruderhof, Schwarzenau Brethren, River Brethren and Apostolic Christians), footwashing is regularly practiced as an ordinance, in obedience to Jesus's command in John 13:1–17.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The early Church practiced footwashing, in addition to the Holy Kiss, prior to reception of the Eucharist.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] A cantharus is a fountain used by Christians for ablution before entering a church.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] These ablutions involve the washing of the hands, head, and feet.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The cantharus is traditionally located in the exonarthex of the church.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The water emitted by a cantharus is to be running water.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The practice has its origins Jewish practice of performing ablutions before entering into the presence of God (cf.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Though canthari are not as prevalent anymore in Western Christianity, they are found in Eastern Christian and Oriental Christian churches.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Christianity has always placed a strong emphasis on hygiene, and water plays a role in the Christian rituals.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Great bathhouses were built in Byzantine centers such as Constantinople and Antioch, and the popes allocated to the Romans bathing through *diaconia*, or private Lateran baths, or even a myriad of monastic bath houses functioning in eighth and ninth centuries.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Public bathing were common in medieval Christendom larger towns and cities such as Paris, Regensburg and Naples.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Catholic religious orders of the Augustinians' and Benedictines' rules contained ritual purification, and inspired by Benedict of Nursia encouragement for the practice of therapeutic bathing; Benedictine monks played a role in the development and promotion of spas.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Protestant Christianity also played a prominent role in the development of the British spas.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] In circa 1454 pope Nicholas V commissioned building a bath palace in Viterbo, and the construction at the *Bagno del Papa* was continued on through the reigns of several popes after Nicholas V.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The Vatican accounts mention of payments "for building done at the bath palace of Viterbo" during the reigns of Calixtus III, Paul II, and Sixtus IV.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] There also is evidence Pope Pius II was responsible for the addition of a western wing to the building.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Contrary to popular belief bathing and sanitation were not lost in Europe with the collapse of the Roman Empire, as the spread of the Black Death made "Medieval people look for a link between health and hygiene".
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] By the 15th century, the manufacture of soap in the Christendom had become virtually industrialized, with sources in Antwerp, Castile, Marseille, Naples and Venice.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The Salvation Army has adopted movement of the deployment of the personal hygiene, and by providing personal hygiene products, such as a toothbrush, toothpaste, and soap.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Believing that on Epiphany day water becomes holy and is imbued with special powers, Eastern Orthodox cut holes in the ice of lakes and rivers, often in the shape of the cross, to bathe in the freezing water.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Christianity strongly affected the development of holy wells in Europe and the Middle East, and its water are known for its healing properties.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The use of water in many Christian countries is due in part to the Biblical toilet etiquette which encourages washing after all instances of defecation.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The bidet is common in predominantly Catholic countries where water is considered essential for anal cleansing, and in some traditionally Orthodox and Lutheran countries such as Greece and Finland respectively, where bidet showers are common.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] In the Roman Rite, the celebrant washes his hands before vesting for Mass, but with another prayer (*Da, Domine, virtutem*).
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] He will then wash his hands again after the offertory—this is the ceremony that is known as the *lavabo* proper.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] This washing appears in both the Tridentine Mass, and in the Mass of Paul VI.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The reason for this "second" washing of hands probably developed from the long ceremony of receiving the loaves and vessels of wine from the people at the offertory that was used in Rome.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] In the Gallican Rite the offerings were prepared before Mass began, as in the Eastern Liturgy of Preparation, so there was no long version of the offertory nor place for a lavabo before the Eucharistic Prayer.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] In the Middle Ages, the Roman Rite actually had two washing of hands, one before and one after the offertory.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] This first one has since disappeared, and the one which remains is the second.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] In the Tridentine Mass, as well as in Lutheran Masses of Evangelical Catholic churchmanship and in Anglican Masses of Anglo-Catholic churchmanship, the term "ablutions" refers to when the priest rinses his hands first in wine and then in water following the Communion.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] It is to be distinguished from the lavabo, when the celebrant washes his hands with water only, reciting the words of Psalm 26:6–12 (KJV—in the Septuagint it is Psalm 25) at the offertory.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] In the common Mass of Paul VI, the Lutheran Divine Service and the Anglican Eucharist the priest does not normally use wine to wash his hands at the ablution, although this is permitted, but only water.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Prior to praying the canonical hours at seven fixed prayer times, Oriental Orthodox Christians wash their hands, face and feet (cf.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] In the Eastern Orthodox and Greek-Catholic Churches, the term "ablution" refers to consuming the remainder of the Gifts (the Body and Blood of Christ) at the end of the Divine Liturgy.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Holy Communion is always received in both Species (the Body and the Blood of Christ) not only by the clergy but also by the faithful.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] This is accomplished by placing the particles of the consecrated Lamb (bread) into the chalice, and distributing Communion to the faithful with a spoon.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The portion which remains in the chalice afterwards must be consumed.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The ablutions will normally be performed by the deacon, but if no deacon is serving the priest will do them.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] After the Litany of Thanksgiving that follows Communion, the deacon will come into the sanctuary and kneel, placing his forehead on the Holy Table (Altar) and the priest will bless him to consume the Gifts, which is done at the Prothesis (Table of Oblation).
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] First, using the liturgical spoon he will consume all of the Body and Blood of Christ which remain in the chalice.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Then he will pour hot water on the diskos (paten), which is then poured into the chalice and consumed (this is to consume any particles that may remain on the diskos).
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Next the liturgical spear, spoon and chalice will be rinsed first with wine and then with hot water, which are then consumed.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] All of the sacred vessels are then wiped dry with a towel, wrapped in their cloth coverings and put away.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Because the ablutions necessarily require consuming the Holy Mysteries (the Body and Blood of Christ), a priest or deacon may only perform them after having fully prepared himself through fasting and the lengthy Preparation for Holy Communion.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] If the Reserved Mysteries should become moldy, they must still be consumed in the same manner as the ablutions after Liturgy (normally, a fair amount of wine would be poured over them before consuming them, in order to soften and disinfect them).
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] To prevent this, when the Mysteries are to be reserved for the sick, they should be thoroughly dried before being placed in the Tabernacle.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] In Orthodox Christianity, there is also an ablution performed on the eighth day after Baptism.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Immediately after being Baptized, every person, including an infant, is confirmed using the Mystery (Sacrament) of Chrismation.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] In the early church, the places where the person was anointed with Chrism were carefully bandaged, and were kept covered for eight days.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] During this period, the newly illumined (newly baptized person) would also wear his baptismal robe every day.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] At the end of the eight days, the priest would remove the bandages and baptismal garment and perform ablutions over him.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] While the bandaging no longer takes place, the ritual ablutions are still performed.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The newly illumined (newly baptized person) is brought back to the church by his Godparents for the ablutions.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The priest stands him in the center of the church, in front of the Holy Doors, facing east.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] He loosens the belt of the baptismal robe and prays for him, that God may preserve the newly illumined in purity and illumine him by grace.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] He then dips a sponge in water and sprinkles him in the sign of the cross saying: "Thou art justified.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Thou art washed: in the name of the Father, and of the Son, and of the Holy Spirit.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Amen." Then, as he says the next prayer, he washes each of the places where he had been anointed with Chrism.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Next he performs the Tonsure, symbolic of the life of self-sacrifice a Christian must lead.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] In modern practice, these ablutions are performed at the end of the baptism service, after the first reception of Holy Communion.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Many Christian churches practice a ceremony of the Washing of Feet, following the example of Jesus in the Gospel.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Some interpret this as an ordinance which the church is obliged to practice, as with Anabaptist Christianity (inclusive of Mennonites, Amish, Hutterites, Bruderhof, Schwarzenau Brethren, River Brethren and Apostolic Christians).
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Benedict of Nursia lays out in his Rule that the feet of visitors to the monastery should be washed, and also that those who are assigned to serve in the kitchen that week should wash the feet of all the brethren.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] At one time, most of the European monarchs also performed the Washing of Feet in their royal courts on Maundy Thursday, a practice continued by the Austro-Hungarian Emperor and the King of Spain up to the beginning of the 20th century (see Royal Maundy).
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Foot washing is also observed by numerous traditions, including Anabaptists, Seventh-day Adventist, Pentecostal, and Radical Pietistic groups, and several types of Southern Baptists.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Often in these services, the bishop will wash the feet of the clergy, and in monasteries the Abbot will wash the feet of the brethren.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Though history shows that foot washing has at times been practiced in connection with baptism, and at times as a separate occasion, by far its most common practice has been in connection with the Lord's supper service.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The Moravian Church practiced Foot Washing until 1818.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] There has been some revival of the practice as other liturgical churches have also rediscovered the practice.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] When an Orthodox Christian dies, their body is washed and dressed before burial.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Although this custom is not considered to impose any sort of ritual purity, it is an important aspect of charitable care for the departed.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Ideally, this should not be deferred to an undertaker, but should be performed by family members or friends of the deceased.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] When an Orthodox priest or bishop dies, these ablutions and vesting are performed by the clergy, saying the same prayers for each vestment that are said when the departed bishop or priest vested for the Divine Liturgy.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] After the body of a Bishop is washed and vested, he is seated in a chair and the Dikirion and Trikirion are placed in his hands for the final time.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] When an Orthodox monk dies, his body is washed and clothed in his monastic habit by brethren of his monastery.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] When an Orthodox nun dies, the sisterhood of her convent performs the same ministrations for her as are done for monks.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] In the Roman Catholic Church, the Absolute (or *absolution of the dead*) is a symbolic ablution of the deceased's body following the Requiem Mass.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] While specific prayers are said, the coffin is incensed and sprinkled with holy water.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The absolution of the dead is only performed in context of the Tridentine Mass.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Following the Second Vatican Council, the absolution of the dead was removed from the funeral liturgy of the Mass of Paul VI.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Washing and anointing (also called the *initiatory*) is a temple ordinance practiced by the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church) and Mormon fundamentalists as part of the faith's endowment ceremony.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] It is a purification ritual for adults, usually performed at least a year after baptism.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The ordinance is performed by the authority of the Melchizedek priesthood by an officiator of the same sex as the participant.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] In the ritual, a person is sprinkled with water to symbolically wash away the "blood and sins of this generation".
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] After the washing, the person is then anointed to become a "king and priest" or a "queen and priestess" in the afterlife.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Once washed and anointed, the participant is dressed in the temple garment, a religious undergarment which the participant is instructed to wear throughout his or her life.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] (Since 2005, participants in the LDS Church version of the ritual already come clothed in this garment prior to the washing and anointing.) Finally, the participant is given a "new name" which he or she is instructed never to reveal except under certain conditions in the temple.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] Mormons link the ritual to biblical washings and anointings.
[src:crusades/ablution-in-christianity] The temple garment symbolizes the skins of clothing given to Adam and Eve in the Garden of Eden, and the "new name" is linked to Revelation 2:17, which states that God will give those who overcome "a white stone with a new name written on it, known only to him who receives it".
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] Nothing is known of his family background.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] He may have been born in Venice, as his surname implies, but it is possible that he acquired the name by joining the Franciscan convent of Santa Maria Gloriosa dei Frari in Venice.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] He is first recorded in the *Liber contractuum* of the Franciscans of Padua as a student in their *studium* on 12 December 1293.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] In 1301, Paolino was a lecturer in theology at Venice.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] He was present on 30 November when the inquisitor Antonio da Padova confronted Doge Pietro Gradenigo over the introduction of the inquisition into Venice.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] On 12 August 1302, in his capacity as guardian of Santa Maria Gloriosa dei Frari, he was ordered by the papal legate Guy de Neuville to hand over the money which the inquisitor Alessandro Novello had given to the convent.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] By 1304 he was a *custos* in the Franciscan province of Venice.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] On 5 October, he was present in the church of San Francesco in Treviso to witness the agreement ending the Salt War between Padua and Venice.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] Between 1305 and 1308, Paolino was an inquisitor in the March of Treviso.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] In 1307–1308, he was investigated by the canonist Giovanni d'Andrea and the legate Guillaume de Balait after he was accused by Ainardo da Ceneda of accepting bribes.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] He allegedly spent the money on parchment and books.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] By March 1308, he was again lecturing in Venice.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] On 24 October, Guillaume de Balait authorized Bishop Pagano della Torre to release Paolino from his excommunication if he repaid 300 gold florins by Christmas.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] Paolino is not mentioned in any source for the next seven years.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] On 22 September 1315, he is listed as a citizen of the commune of Treviso.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] In 1315–1316 and 1320, he was the diplomatic representative of the Republic of Venice to the court of King Robert of Naples.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] The first mission, coming while Venice was under interdict for its part in the War of Ferrara, resulted in a treaty between Venice and Naples.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] The second mission took him to Provence, where Robert was staying.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] He secured compensation for damages inflicted on a Venetian ship by Genoese pirates, Genoa being under Robert's rule at the time.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] Around 1321, Paolino was named to the Apostolic Penitentiary, then at Avignon in Provence.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] On 24 September 1321, Paolino was charged by Pope John XXII with examining the *Liber secretorum fidelium crucis*, a treatise on a new crusade submitted by Marino Sanudo Torsello.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] Paolino and three others examined the work in Paolino's house in Avignon.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] From 1322 to 1326, Paolino served as the papal ambassador to Venice.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] In this capacity, he also dealt with the Visconti of Milan, the Este of Ferrara and the city of Fano, which were all under Venetian protection and papal interdict at the time.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] His first mission was to end hostilities between Venice and Rimini.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] His second was to Ferrara, which was then in revolt against the papal rule.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] In 1324, Paolino was elected bishop of Pozzuoli in the Kingdom of Naples, possibly through intervention of the king.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] He was consecrated by Cardinal Bertrand de la Tour.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] He did not arrive in Pozzuoli until 1326, after his last diplomatic mission to Venice.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] From 1328 until his death, he served as an important advisor on the royal council.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] There is relatively little information on his activities as bishop.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] Several letters he received from Marino Sanudo survive from this time.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] It was also during this period that he met Giovanni Boccaccio in Naples.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] Paolino divided his time as bishop between Pozzuoli and the royal court in Naples.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] The date of death is not known, but it took place before 22 June, the date of a papal inventory of his belongings.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] In accordance with the papal right of spoil, some of his books made their way to the Papal Library in Avignon.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] Paolino's earliest work is *Trattato de regimine rectoris* ('treatise on the conduct of a lord').
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] It is a treatise on government of the mirror for princes genre.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] It was written between 1313 and 1315 in Venetian (with a Latin prologue) and dedicated to the Venetian duke of Candia, a member of the Badoer family named Marino.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] It is divided into three sections on governing oneself, governing one's family and political governance.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] Its structure and content are based on the *De regimine principum* of Giles of Rome or possibly on the French translation by Henri de Gauchi.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] Compared to Giles, Paolino is pithy and practical.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] Paolino wrote three universal chronicles in Latin.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] He worked on the project from 1306 to 1331.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] In chronological order the three are the *Epithoma*, *Compendium* and *Satirica*.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] The impetus for Paolino to write an expanded version of his *Epithoma*, which resulted in the *Compendium* and *Satirica*, was his meeting with Marino Sanudo and his review of Sanudo's *Liber secretorum*, which resulted in a correspondence between the two.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] These interactions broadened Paolino's geographical scope.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] No complete edition of any of the chronicles exists, owing in part to the complexity of the manuscripts, which are replete with large tables.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] Certain excerpts have been extracted and published separately.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] Paolino was widely used as a source in the 14th and 15th centuries.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] His contemporary, Andrea Dandolo, cites the *Satirica* in his *Chronica per extensum descripta*.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] He was also used by Poggio Bracciolini, Coluccio Salutati and Jan Długosz.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] Boccaccio had a mixed opinion of Paolino as a historian.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] In the eighth chapter of Book XIV of his *Genealogie deorum gentilium*, published around 1363, he praised him, but he left critical remarks in his own copy of Paolino's *Compendium*.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] He considered him often to be, in the words of Roberta Morosini, "confused and ignorant".
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] Nonetheless, he copied the account of the life of Muḥammad in Paolino's *Satirica* into one of his notebooks, the *Zibaldone Magliabechiano*, under the title *De Maumeth propheta Saracenorum*.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] The *Epithoma* and *Satirica* today are not highly valued for their historical information.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] The *Compendium*, however, does contain some valuable information on early Franciscan history.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] The so-called fifth biography of Pope Clement V (1305–1314) and the fourth of John XXII (1316–1334) are in fact extracts from the *Satirica* that circulated independently.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] Paolino's works on the Franciscans are more valuable today as sources of information than his universal chronicles.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] His *Provinciale ordinis fratrum minorum* catalogues the provinces, custodies and convents of the contemporary Franciscan order.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] Paolino is probably also responsible for compiling the *Liber privilegiorum ordinis Minorum* found in the manuscript Pontificia Biblioteca Antoniana, MS 49.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] Written around 1323, it contains copies of papal privileges granted to the Franciscans.
[src:crusades/abreujamen-de-las-estorias] Paolino also wrote an outline of the ecclesiastical provinces and diocese subject to Rome, entitled *Provinciale Romanae curiae*.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] The number of absolute monarchies in the world varies but some datasets agree that Brunei, Eswatini, Oman, Qatar, and Saudi Arabia are absolute monarchies, while others include Bahrain, Bhutan, Jordan, Kuwait, Liechtenstein, Monaco, Morocco, Tonga, Vatican City and the United Arab Emirates.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Absolute monarchies are distinct from hereditary dictatorships such as North Korea, Duvalier Haiti or Ba'athist Syria.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] In the Ottoman Empire, the Sultan wielded absolute power over the state and was considered a Padishah, meaning "Great King" by his people.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Many sultans wielded absolute power through heavenly mandates reflected in their titles, such as "Shadow of God on Earth".
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] In ancient Mesopotamia, many rulers of Assyria, Babylonia and Sumer were absolute monarchs as well.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Throughout Imperial China, many emperors and one empress (Wu Zetian) wielded absolute power through the Mandate of Heaven.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] In pre-Columbian America, the Inca Empire was ruled by a Sapa Inca, who was considered the son of Inti, the sun god and absolute ruler over the people and nation.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Korea under the Joseon dynasty and short-lived empire was also an absolute monarchy.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Throughout much of European history, the divine right of kings was the theological justification for absolute monarchy.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Many European monarchs claimed supreme autocratic power by divine right, and that their subjects had no rights to limit their power.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] James VI and I and his son Charles I tried to import the principle of divine right into Scotland and England.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] This law consequently authorized the king to abolish all other centers of power.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Most important was the abolition of the Council of the Realm in Denmark.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Absolute monarchy lasted until 1814 in Norway, and 1848 in Denmark.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] The House of Habsburg is currently extinct in its male line, due to the death of the childless Charles II of Spain in 1700.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] However, the House of Habsburg-Lorraine still carries the female line of the House of Habsburg.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] The first member of the House of Habsburg-Lorraine to rule over the Holy Roman Empire was Joseph II, a sovereign raised during the Enlightenment.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Joseph II extended full legal freedom to serfs in 1781.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Franz Joseph I of Austria was Emperor of Austria from 1848 until his death in 1916 and was succeeded by Charles I of Austria.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Charles I was the last Emperor of Austria and abdicated on 12 November 1918 due to Austria-Hungary losing World War I.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Louis XIV (1638–1715) is said to have proclaimed *L'état, c'est moi!*, 'I am the State!'.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Although often criticized for his extravagances, such as the Palace of Versailles, he reigned over France for a long period.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] The king of France concentrated legislative, executive, and judicial powers in his person.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] He could condemn people to death without the right of appeal.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] It was both his duty to punish offenses and stop them from being committed.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] From his judicial authority followed his power both to make laws and to annul them.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] In Brandenburg-Prussia, the concept of absolute monarch took a notable turn from the above with its emphasis on the monarch as the "first servant of the state", but it also echoed many of the important characteristics of absolutism.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Prussia was ruled by the House of Hohenzollern as a feudal monarchy from 1525 to 1701 and an absolute monarchy from 1701 to 1848, after which it became a federal semi-constitutional monarchy from 1848 to 1918 until the monarchy was abolished during the German Revolution.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Frederick I was the first *King in Prussia*, beginning his reign on 18 January 1701.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] King Frederick the Great adopted the title *King of Prussia* in 1772, the same year he annexed most of Royal Prussia in the First Partition of Poland, and practiced enlightened absolutism until his death in 1786.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] He introduced a general civil code, abolished torture and established the principle that the Crown would not interfere in matters of justice.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] He also promoted an advanced secondary education, the forerunner of today's German gymnasium (grammar school) system, which prepares high achieving students for university studies.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] The Prussian education system was emulated in various countries, including the United States.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Until 1905, the tsars and emperors of Russia governed as absolute monarchs.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Ivan IV ("the Terrible") was known for his reign of terror through the *oprichnina*.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Following the Time of Troubles in the early 17th century, the traditional alliance of autocratic monarchy, the church, and the aristocracy was widely seen as the only basis for preserving the social order and Russian statehood, which legitimized the rule of the Romanov dynasty.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Peter I ("the Great") reduced the power of the Russian nobility and strengthened the central power of the monarch, establishing a bureaucracy.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] This tradition of absolutism was expanded by Catherine II and her descendants.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Russia became the last European country (excluding Vatican City) to abolish absolutism, and it was the only one to do so as late as the 20th century (the Ottoman Empire drafted its first constitution in 1876).
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Russia was one of the four continental empires which collapsed after World War I, along with Germany, Austria–Hungary, and the Ottoman Empire.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] In 1918, the Bolsheviks executed the Romanov family, ending three centuries of Romanov rule.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] The Revolutions of 1848, known in some countries as the *Springtime of the Peoples* or the *Springtime of Nations*, were a series of political upheavals throughout Europe in 1848.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Many nations formerly with absolute monarchies, such as Jordan, Kuwait, Morocco and Qatar, have *de jure* moved towards a constitutional monarchy.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] However, in these cases, the monarch still retains tremendous powers, even to the extent that by some measures, parliament's influence on political life is viewed as negligible or merely consultative.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] In Nepal, there were several swings between constitutional rule and direct rule related to the Nepalese Civil War, the Maoist insurgency, and the 2001 Nepalese royal massacre, with the Nepalese monarchy being abolished on 28 May 2008.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] In Tonga, the king had majority control of the Legislative Assembly until 2010.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Liechtenstein has moved towards expanding the power of the monarch—the Prince of Liechtenstein was given vast expanded powers after a referendum to amend the Constitution of Liechtenstein in 2003, which led BBC News to describe the prince as an "absolute monarch again".
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] The referendum granted the monarch the powers to dismiss the government, nominate judges and veto legislation, among others.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Just prior to the referendum, the Venice Commission of the Council of Europe published a comprehensive report analysing the amendments, opining that they were not compatible with the European standards of democracy, effectively making Liechtenstein a *de facto* absolute monarchy.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Prince Hans-Adam II had also previously threatened to leave the country and move his assets out of Liechtenstein if voters had chosen to restrict his powers.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Vatican City continues to be an absolute monarchy, but is unique because it is also a microstate, ecclesiastical jurisdiction, and elective monarchy.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] As of 2023, Vatican City has a population of 764 residents (regardless of citizenship).
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] It is the smallest state in the world both by area and by population.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] The Pope is the absolute monarch of Vatican City, and is elected by a papal conclave with a two-thirds supermajority.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] As governed by the Holy See, Vatican City State is an sacerdotal-monarchical state ruled by the Pope, who is the bishop of Rome and head of the Catholic Church.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Unlike citizenship of other states, which is based either on *jus sanguinis* or *jus soli*, citizenship of Vatican City is granted on *jus officii*, namely on the grounds of appointment to work in a certain capacity in the service of the Holy See.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] It usually ceases upon cessation of the appointment.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Citizenship is also extended to the spouse and children of a citizen, provided they are living together in the city.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Saudi Arabia is an absolute monarchy, and according to the Basic Law of Saudi Arabia adopted by Royal Decree in 1992, the King must comply with Sharia (Islamic law) and the Quran.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] No political parties or national elections are permitted.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] The Saudi government is the world's most authoritarian regime in 2023 measured by the electoral democracy score of the V-Dem Democracy indices.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Oman is an absolute monarchy, with the sultan of Oman being both head of state and head of government.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] The sultan is hereditary, who appoints a cabinet to assist him.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] The sultan also serves as the supreme commander of the armed forces and prime minister.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] There is a considerable variety of opinion by historians on the extent of absolutism among European monarchs.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Some, such as Perry Anderson, argue that quite a few monarchs achieved levels of absolutist control over their states, while historians such as Roger Mettam dispute the very concept of absolutism.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] In the 17th century, French legal theorist Jean Domat defended the concept of absolute monarchy in works such as *"On Social Order and Absolute Monarchy"*, citing absolute monarchy as preserving natural order as God intended.
[src:crusades/absolute-monarchy] Other intellectual figures who supported absolute monarchy include Thomas Hobbes and Charles Maurras.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] The **Crusades** were a series of military campaigns launched by the papacy between 1095 and 1291 against Muslim rulers for the recovery and defence of the Holy Land, as part of a wider crusading movement.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] The First Crusade was proclaimed by Pope Urban II at the Council of Clermont in November 1095—a call to arms for Christians to reconquer Jerusalem from the Muslims, with promises of spiritual reward.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] By this time, the papacy's position as head of the Catholic Church had strengthened, and earlier conflicts with secular rulers and wars on the frontiers of Western Christendom had prepared it for the direction of armed force in religious causes.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] The successes of the First Crusade led to the establishment of four Crusader states in the Levant, where their defence required further expeditions from Catholic Europe.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] The organisation of such large-scale campaigns demanded complex religious, social, and economic institutions, including crusade indulgences, military orders, and the taxation of clerical income.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Over time, the crusading movement expanded to include campaigns against pagans, Christian dissidents, and other enemies of the papacy, promoted with similar spiritual rewards and continuing into the 18th century.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] The Crusade of 1101, the earliest papally sanctioned expedition inspired by the First Crusade, ended in disastrous defeats.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] For several decades thereafter, only smaller expeditions reached the Holy Land, yet their role in consolidating and expanding the Crusader states was pivotal.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] The fall of Edessa, the capital of the first Crusader state, prompted the Second Crusade, which failed in 1148.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Its failure reduced support for crusading across Latin Christendom, leaving the Crusader states unable to resist Saladin's expansion.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Having united Egypt and Muslim Syria under his rule, Saladin destroyed their combined armies at the Battle of Hattin in 1187.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] The Crusader states survived largely owing to the Third Crusade, a major campaign against Saladin, though Jerusalem remained under Muslim control.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Initially directed against Egypt, the Fourth Crusade was diverted to the Byzantine Empire, culminating in the Sack of Constantinople and the establishment of the Latin Empire in 1204.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] The Fifth Crusade again targeted Egypt but failed to conquer it in 1219–21.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] By this period, crusade indulgences could also be obtained through other campaigns—such as the Iberian, Albigensian, and Northern Crusades—thereby diminishing enthusiasm for expeditions in the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Jerusalem was regained through negotiation during the Sixth Crusade in 1229, and in 1239–41 the Barons' Crusade restored much of the territory the Crusader states had lost.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] However, the Sack of Jerusalem by Muslim freebooters soon ended Crusader rule in the Holy City.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Louis IX of France launched two major campaigns—the Seventh Crusade against Egypt in 1248–51 and the Eighth Crusade against Tunis in 1270—both of which ended in failure.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] In place of the large-scale *passagium generale*, the smaller *passagium particulare* became the predominant form of crusading campaigns in the late 13th century.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] The Crusader states, however, were unable to withstand the advance of the Mamluks.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Having reunited Egypt and Muslim Syria by 1260, they went on to attack the Crusader states, capturing the Crusaders' last mainland strongholds in 1291.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Although plans for the reconquest of the Holy Land continued to be made in the following decades, only the Alexandrian Crusade briefly revived crusading activity in the region in 1365.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] The Crusades were military campaigns undertaken by Western Christians to reclaim the Holy Land, or Palestine, from Muslim control between the 11th and 13th centuries.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Launched by the papacy with promises of spiritual reward, they were occasionally accompanied by unauthorised movements—driven by popular zeal—commonly referred to as popular crusades.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] In scholarly usage, the term is frequently applied more broadly to include papally authorised conflicts in other regions, conducted within the wider framework of the crusading movement, including the Iberian, Northern and Albigensian Crusades.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Terminology evolved gradually, primarily reflecting the close association between the Crusades and Christian pilgrimage.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Early usage favoured terms denoting mobility—*iter* ('journey'), *expeditio* ('expedition'), *passagium* ('passage')—typically accompanied by references to the intended destination, such as the Church of the Holy Sepulchre in Jerusalem.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Other early expressions invoked the cross (*crux*), and by around 1250, canon lawyers were distinguishing between campaigns in the Holy Land—*crux transmarina* ('the cross overseas')—and those within Europe—*crux cismarina* ('the cross this side of the sea').
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Participants, who traditionally sewed a cross onto their garments, came to be known as *crucesignati* ('those signed with the cross').
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Vernacular terminology reflected the ritual of "taking the cross".
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] The earliest attested form, *crozada*, appeared in Spain in 1212.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] The Middle English *croiserie*, derived from Old French, emerged in the 13th–14th centuries, later supplanted by forms such as *croisade* and *crusado*, both influenced by Spanish through French.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] The modern term *crusade* was established by 1706.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] The medievalist Thomas Asbridge notes that the term's conventional use by historians imposes "a somewhat misleading aura of coherence and conformity" on the earliest crusading efforts.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Sites linked to Jesus's ministry became popular pilgrimage destinations in Roman Palestine.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Christian emperors built churches at these locations, including the Church of the Holy Sepulchre, marking Jesus's crucifixion and resurrection in Jerusalem.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] In 395, the Roman Empire split into eastern and western halves.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] The Western Roman Empire had fragmented into smaller kingdoms by 476, while the Eastern Roman (Byzantine) Empire persisted, though it lost vast territories to the rising Islamic Caliphate in the 7th century.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Islamic expansion, motivated by *jihad* (holy war), reached Western Europe with the Muslim conquest of much of the Iberian Peninsula after 711.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Christians under Muslim rule were *dhimmi*—legally protected but socially subordinate.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Islam's ideological unity fractured over disputes about leadership.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] The Shi'a believed authority belonged to the descendants of Muhammad's cousin and son-in-law, Ali, while the Sunni majority rejected the Alids' hereditary claim.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] By the mid-10th century, three rival caliphates had emerged: the Umayyads in al-Andalus (Muslim Spain), the Shi'ite Fatimids in Egypt, and the Abbasids in the Middle East.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] To Muslim observers, such as Ibn Khordadbeh, the remote and less developed Western Europe was merely a source of slaves and raw materials.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] 1070, drought and cold spells across North Africa, the Middle East, and Central Asia led to famine and migration.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Interfaith tensions escalated, culminating in the temporary destruction of the Holy Sepulchre in 1009.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] From the 1040s, nomadic Turkomans disrupted the Middle East.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] In 1055, their leader Tughril I of the Seljuk clan assumed authority within the Abbasid Caliphate with Caliph Al-Qa'im's consent.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Tughril's nephew Alp Arslan crushed the Byzantines at the Battle of Manzikert in 1071, opening Anatolia to Turkoman migration.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] The Seljuk Empire emerged as a loose federation of provinces ruled by Seljuk princes, Turkoman warlords and Arab emirs.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] As Byzantine control collapsed, Armenian and Greek strongmen took over frontier cities and fortresses.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] From the mid-9th century, central authority in Western Europe weakened, and local lords gained power, commanding heavily armoured knights and holding castles.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Their territorial disputes made warfare a regular feature across regions.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] To protect church property and unarmed groups, church leaders launched the Peace of God movement, threatening offenders with excommunication.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] As sins permeated daily life, Christians feared damnation.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Sinners were expected to confess and undertake priestly prescribed penance.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Thousands made the penitential journey to Jerusalem, though attacks on pilgrims became increasingly frequent.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] 1000, the Medieval Warm Period favoured Western Europe, spurring economic and population growth.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Within a century, Italian merchants supplanted their Muslim and Jewish rivals as the leading force in Mediterranean trade.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] In 1031, al-Andalus fragmented into *taifas*—smaller kingdoms—that could not resist the *Reconquista*—the expansion of the northern Christian states—prompting intervention by the radical Almoravids from the Maghreb.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] In southern Italy, Norman warriors from northern France founded principalities and completed the conquest of Muslim Sicily by 1091.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] In the mid-11th century, clerics promoting the "liberty of the Church" rose to power in Rome, banning simony and clerical marriage.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] The popes, regarded as successors to Saint Peter in Rome, claimed supremacy over Christendom, but Eastern Christian leaders rejected this.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Combined with long-standing liturgical and theological differences, this led to mutual excommunications in 1054 and ultimately the division between the Catholic West and Orthodox East.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Reformist clerics' rejection of lay control triggered the Investiture Controversy with secular powers.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Popes had already courted allies by offering spiritual rewards, and the Controversy revived interest in the theology of just war, first articulated by Augustine in the 5th century.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Theologians, under Pope Gregory VII's auspices, concluded that dying in a just war equated to martyrdom.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Still, the idea of penitential warfare drew sharp criticism from anti-papal figures like Sigebert of Gembloux.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] By the late 11th century, the development of Christian just war theory, increasing aristocratic piety, and the popularity of penitential journeys to the Holy Land created a context for armed pilgrimages.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Strengthened by the church reforms, the papacy was well positioned to channel anxiety over sin and hopes of remission into a papally orchestrated war.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] In 1074, Gregory VII was the first pope to plan a campaign against the Turkomans, though it was never launched.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] In March 1095, his successor, Urban II, received envoys from Emperor Alexios I Komnenos, who requested military aid at the Council of Piacenza.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] By this time, the Seljuk Empire had descended into civil war following the deaths of *Vizier* Nizam al-Mulk and Sultan Malik-Shah I in 1092.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Malik-Shah's brother Tutush I contested the succession of Malik-Shah's son Berkyaruq.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Although Tutush was killed in battle in 1095, his sons Ridwan and Duqaq, seized control of the Syrian cities of Aleppo and Damascus, respectively, while Tutush's former *mamluk* (slave soldier), Yaghi-Siyan, maintained his rule over Antioch.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] In Anatolia, the breakaway Seljuk prince Kilij Arslan I founded the independent Sultanate of Rum, while an autonomous Turkoman clan, the Danishmendids, seized control of the north.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Meanwhile, Fatimid Egypt faced its own succession crisis after the deaths of Caliph al-Mustansir and his *vizier* al-Jamali.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Al-Jamali's son and successor al-Afdal Shahanshah installed al-Mustansir's youngest son al-Musta'li as caliph bypassing the eldest son Nizar.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Although Nizar was murdered, his supporters rejected al-Musta'li's legitimacy and established a new branch of radical Shi'a Islam—the Nizaris, also known as the Assassins.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] In July 1095, Pope Urban began a tour of France, negotiating with local elites, and ending with the Council of Clermont.
[src:crusades/crusades-p01] Here, on 27 November, he announced a military campaign against the Turkomans.
